<root>
  <chapter id="ch2" title="Atomic Structure">
    <topic id="ch2-topic2.1" title="Structure of Atom">
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-cd" type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          The atom is the fundamental building block of matter, consisting of a dense central nucleus (containing protons and neutrons) surrounded by a cloud of electrons that occupy specific energy levels or shells. Though once thought indivisible, atoms are composed of these subatomic particles held together by electromagnetic and nuclear forces.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Bohr model of an atom (e.g., Lithium) showing nucleus with protons/neutrons and electrons in distinct shells - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Quantum mechanical model showing electron cloud probabilities around a nucleus - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exp" type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          The concept of the atom has evolved dramatically over centuries. Ancient Greek philosopher Democritus first proposed that all matter consists of indivisible particles he called "atoms." However, it wasn't until the 19th century that John Dalton provided experimental evidence supporting the existence of atoms through his work with chemical compounds.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          The late 19th century brought revolutionary discoveries through discharge tube experiments, where scientists passed electricity through gases at reduced pressure. These experiments revealed that atoms were not the smallest particles of matter as previously believed. Instead, they discovered electrons (negatively charged particles) and protons (positively charged particles). Later experiments identified neutrons (particles with no charge but similar mass to protons).
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Simple diagram of a cathode ray tube experiment leading to discovery of electrons - necessity_score: 6/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          The modern understanding of atomic structure began with Rutherford's gold foil experiment in 1911, which demonstrated that atoms have a tiny, dense nucleus containing protons and neutrons. This nucleus is surrounded by electrons that occupy specific orbits or shells according to Bohr's atomic model proposed in 1913. Each shell corresponds to a specific energy level, with electrons in shells farther from the nucleus possessing higher energy.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Rutherford's gold foil experiment setup and results (most alpha particles pass through, some deflect, few bounce back) - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          Today's quantum mechanical model depicts electrons not as discrete particles in fixed orbits but as probability clouds, where we can only predict the likelihood of finding an electron at a particular location around the nucleus. Despite their incredibly small size, atoms follow organized principles of structure that determine the properties of all matter in our universe.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-av" type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Solar System Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Solar System Analogy</emphasis>: Think of an atom as a miniature solar system. The nucleus represents the sun at the center, while electrons orbit around it like planets. However, unlike planets, electrons don't follow fixed paths but exist as probability clouds, and they're held in place by electrical forces rather than gravity.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Atom depicted as a solar system (nucleus as sun, electrons as planets in orbits) - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Stadium Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Stadium Analogy</emphasis>: If an atom were enlarged to the size of a football stadium, the nucleus would be smaller than a marble at the center field. The electrons would be like tiny gnats flying around in the stands. This illustrates how atoms are mostly empty space, with a tiny but extremely dense nucleus holding most of the mass.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Visual scale comparison: stadium representing atom, marble representing nucleus - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ex" type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Hydrogen Atom">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Hydrogen Atom</emphasis>: The simplest atom with atomic number 1, containing 1 proton in its nucleus and 1 electron in its first shell. It has no neutrons in its most common form (protium isotope). This demonstrates the basic atomic structure of a single electron orbiting a nucleus.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Oxygen Atom">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Oxygen Atom</emphasis>: With atomic number 8, oxygen has 8 protons and typically 8 neutrons in its nucleus, with 8 electrons arranged in two shells (2 in the first shell and 6 in the second shell). This shows how electrons fill successive shells according to specific patterns.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="Uranium Atom">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Uranium Atom</emphasis>: With atomic number 92, uranium has 92 protons and approximately 146 neutrons, with electrons arranged across seven shells. As a heavy, naturally radioactive element, uranium demonstrates how complex atomic structures can become unstable, emitting radiation as they decay into lighter elements.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Bohr models for Hydrogen, Oxygen, and a simplified Uranium atom showing shells and electron counts - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-rla" type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Nuclear Energy">
          <paragraph>Understanding atomic structure, particularly the nucleus and isotopes (like Uranium-235), is fundamental to harnessing nuclear energy through fission in power plants.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Medical Imaging (MRI)">
          <paragraph>Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) relies on the magnetic properties of atomic nuclei (specifically hydrogen protons) to create detailed images of the inside of the human body.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Semiconductors and Electronics">
          <paragraph>The electronic structure of atoms, especially elements like silicon and germanium, determines their semiconductor properties, which are the basis for all modern electronics, including computers and smartphones.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Lasers">
          <paragraph>Lasers work based on stimulating electrons in atoms to jump between specific energy levels and emit coherent light, a direct application of understanding electron shells and energy transitions.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ie" type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.1.ie1">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Thought Experiment</emphasis>: If atoms are mostly empty space, why can't your hand pass through a solid table? Research quantum mechanical principles that explain this phenomenon.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.1.ie2">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Investigation</emphasis>: Research and draw models showing how our understanding of atomic structure has evolved from Dalton's solid sphere model to today's quantum mechanical model. What key experiments drove these changes?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.1.ie3">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Application Question</emphasis>: How would changing the number of neutrons in an atom affect its chemical properties versus changing the number of electrons? Explain your reasoning based on atomic structure principles.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.1.ie4">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Exploration Challenge</emphasis>: The discharge tube experiments required low gas pressure to observe cathode rays. Why wouldn't these phenomena be observable at atmospheric pressure? Research and explain.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-kps" type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Atoms consist of three fundamental particles: protons (positive charge), neutrons (no charge), and electrons (negative charge).</point>
          <point>Nearly all of an atom's mass is concentrated in its nucleus, though the nucleus occupies less than 1/100,000 of the atom's volume.</point>
          <point>Electrons occupy specific energy levels or shells around the nucleus, with each shell having a maximum electron capacity following the <formula type="math">2n²</formula> formula.</point>
          <point>The first shell (K) can hold 2 electrons, the second shell (L) can hold 8, the third shell (M) can hold 18, and the fourth shell (N) can hold 32.</point>
          <point>Each shell contains subshells (s, p, d, f) that can accommodate specific numbers of electrons (2, 6, 10, and 14 respectively).</point>
          <point>According to modern understanding, electrons behave as probability clouds rather than particles in fixed orbits.</point>
          <point>Atoms are electrically neutral because they contain equal numbers of protons and electrons.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exc" type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="2.1.ex1" level="basic">
