          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-conn" type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Chemical Bonding">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Chemical Bonding</emphasis>: Atomic structure directly determines how elements bond with each other. The arrangement of electrons, particularly in the outermost shell, determines an element's chemical properties and its ability to form compounds.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Periodic Table">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Periodic Table</emphasis>: The organization of the periodic table is based on atomic structure, with elements arranged by increasing atomic number and grouped according to similar electron configurations.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Quantum Physics">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Quantum Physics</emphasis>: The behavior of electrons in atoms forms the foundation of quantum mechanics, which explains phenomena at the subatomic level and has led to technologies like lasers, transistors, and MRI machines.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.1-sec-ff" type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.1.ff1">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Size Perspective</emphasis>: If an atom were enlarged to the size of the Earth, its nucleus would be only about the size of a football stadium! This illustrates the incredible amount of empty space within atoms.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.1.ff2">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Visualization Achievement</emphasis>: Although too small to see with the naked eye, scientists have developed transition electron microscopes powerful enough to actually visualize individual atoms.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.1.ff3">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Element Comparison</emphasis>: The largest atom (cesium) is approximately nine times bigger than the smallest atom (helium), though this difference is in the electron cloud size, not the nucleus.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>

    <topic id="ch2-topic2.2" title="Atomic Number and Mass Number">
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-cd" type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          The atomic number (Z) is the number of protons in an atom's nucleus and uniquely identifies the element, while the mass number (A) represents the total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus. These two numbers define the identity and physical properties of every atom in the universe.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Diagram of a helium atom showing 2 protons (Z=2) and 2 neutrons in nucleus, 2 electrons. Clearly label A (mass number = 4) and Z (atomic number = 2). - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp" type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          While all atoms are made of the same three fundamental particles (electrons, protons, and neutrons), what makes each element unique is the specific number of these particles it contains. The atomic number (Z) represents the number of protons in an atom's nucleus and is the defining characteristic of an element. For example, any atom with 8 protons is oxygen, regardless of how many neutrons or electrons it has.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          Since atoms are electrically neutral, the number of electrons normally equals the number of protons. These electrons determine chemical properties and how elements interact with each other. When an atom gains or loses electrons, it becomes an ion with a negative or positive charge, respectively, but it remains the same element.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          The mass number (A) represents the sum of protons and neutrons in the nucleus. Electrons contribute negligibly to an atom's mass because they're about 1/1836 the mass of a proton. The mass number helps identify specific isotopes of an element and explains why the same element can have different atomic masses.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          When writing atomic symbols, the atomic number appears as a left subscript and the mass number as a left superscript. For example, <formula type="chemical">¹⁶₈O</formula> represents an oxygen atom with 8 protons and 8 neutrons (16-8=8). The number of neutrons can always be calculated using the formula: N = A - Z.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Example of isotopic notation like ¹⁶₈O, with callouts explaining A, Z, and how to find N. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exp-p5" type="paragraph">
          Understanding these numbers is fundamental to chemistry and physics, as they allow scientists to predict an element's behavior, calculate reaction quantities, and understand nuclear processes.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-av" type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Identity Card Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Identity Card Analogy</emphasis>: Think of the atomic number as an element's unique ID number—like a social security number for elements. No matter what else changes about the atom (such as number of neutrons or electrons), as long as it has that specific number of protons, it remains that element.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Building Block Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Building Block Analogy</emphasis>: Imagine atoms as customizable building blocks. The number of protons (atomic number) determines the color of the block (which element it is), while the number of neutrons affects the weight but not the color. Adding or removing electrons changes how blocks connect to each other but not what they fundamentally are.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ex" type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Carbon-12">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Carbon-12</emphasis>: This common isotope of carbon has 6 protons (Z=6) and 6 neutrons, giving it a mass number of 12. It's written as <formula type="chemical">¹²₆C</formula> and is the standard for measuring atomic mass.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Sodium-23">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Sodium-23</emphasis>: Sodium atoms have 11 protons (Z=11) and typically 12 neutrons, giving a mass number of 23. Written as <formula type="chemical">²³₁₁Na</formula>, this element readily loses an electron to form the <formula type="chemical">Na⁺</formula> ion found in table salt.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="Barium-137">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Barium-137</emphasis>: With atomic number 56 and mass number 137, barium (<formula type="chemical">¹³⁷₅₆Ba</formula>) has 56 protons, 56 electrons, and 81 neutrons (137-56=81). This example demonstrates how to calculate neutron numbers for larger elements.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-rla" type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Element Identification">
          <paragraph>Atomic number is the primary way scientists identify elements. Spectroscopic techniques can determine the number of protons in an unknown sample, thus identifying the element(s) present.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Isotope-Specific Applications">
          <paragraph>Mass number is crucial for distinguishing isotopes, which have different numbers of neutrons. For example, Carbon-14 (mass number 14) is used for radiocarbon dating, while Carbon-12 (mass number 12) is stable. This difference is due to neutron count.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Nuclear Medicine and Industry">
          <paragraph>Specific isotopes (defined by their mass numbers) are used in nuclear medicine for diagnosis and treatment (e.g., Iodine-131 for thyroid disorders) and in various industrial applications (e.g., Cobalt-60 for sterilization).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ie" type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.2.ie1">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Calculation Challenge</emphasis>: Element X has a mass number of 55 and 28 neutrons. Identify the element by calculating its atomic number and finding its position on the periodic table.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.2.ie2">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Research Question</emphasis>: Ions are formed when atoms gain or lose electrons. Research how changing the number of electrons affects an atom's size, reactivity, and chemical properties, but doesn't change which element it is.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.2.ie3">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Experimental Design</emphasis>: Design a simple experiment that could demonstrate the difference between changing an atom's electrons (forming ions) versus changing its neutrons (forming isotopes). What properties would you measure?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.2.ie4">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Thought Experiment</emphasis>: If we discovered an atom with 119 protons (beyond current elements), where would it be placed on the periodic table? What properties might it have based on its position?</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-kps" type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>The atomic number (Z) equals the number of protons and uniquely identifies an element.</point>
          <point>In a neutral atom, the number of electrons equals the number of protons.</point>
          <point>The mass number (A) is the sum of protons and neutrons in the nucleus.</point>
          <point>The number of neutrons can be calculated using N = A - Z.</point>
          <point>When writing atomic symbols, the atomic number appears as a left subscript and the mass number as a left superscript (e.g., <formula type="chemical">¹⁶₈O</formula>).</point>
          <point>Changing the number of electrons forms ions, while changing the number of neutrons forms isotopes.</point>
          <point>Almost all of an atom's mass is concentrated in the nucleus (protons and neutrons).</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exc" type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="2.2.ex1" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Basic Exercise</emphasis>: Calculate the number of neutrons in <formula type="chemical">⁵⁶₂₆Fe</formula> (iron-56).</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: N = A - Z = 56 - 26 = 30 neutrons</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="2.2.ex2" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Intermediate Exercise</emphasis>: An atom has 17 protons and 18 neutrons. Write its complete atomic symbol with mass number and atomic number.</paragraph></question>
