        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-conn" type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Periodic Table Structure">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Periodic Table Structure</emphasis>: The atomic number determines an element's position in the periodic table, affecting its chemical properties and relationship to other elements.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Nuclear Chemistry">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Nuclear Chemistry</emphasis>: Understanding atomic numbers and mass numbers is essential for nuclear reactions, radioactive decay processes, and nuclear energy applications.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Quantum Mechanics">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Quantum Mechanics</emphasis>: The atomic number determines the number of electrons and their arrangement in shells and subshells, which directly relates to quantum mechanical principles governing electron behavior.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.2-sec-ff" type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.2.ff1">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Universal Building Blocks</emphasis>: The same elements with the same atomic numbers exist throughout the universe—matter on Mars or distant galaxies consists of the same elements found on Earth!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.2.ff2">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Body Replacement</emphasis>: About 98% of the atoms in your body are replaced every year, yet your atomic numbers stay the same—it's the specific elements that make you, well, you!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="2.2.ff3">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Gallium Surprise</emphasis>: Element 31 (gallium) has such a low melting point (29.8°C/85.6°F) that it will melt in your hand, yet it maintains its atomic number of 31 throughout the phase change.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>

    <topic id="ch2-topic2.3" title="Isotopes and their Masses">
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-cd" type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Isotopes are atoms of the same element (same number of protons) that contain different numbers of neutrons in their nuclei, resulting in different mass numbers. While isotopes share identical chemical properties due to having the same electron configuration, their physical properties vary because of their different masses.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Comparison of Hydrogen isotopes: Protium (1p, 0n), Deuterium (1p, 1n), Tritium (1p, 2n), showing nucleus and single electron. - necessity_score: 10/10] -->
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exp" type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          All atoms of a particular element must have the same number of protons (atomic number), but they can have varying numbers of neutrons in their nuclei. These different versions of the same element are called isotopes. For example, carbon has three common isotopes: carbon-12, carbon-13, and carbon-14, represented as <formula type="chemical">¹²C</formula>, <formula type="chemical">¹³C</formula>, and <formula type="chemical">¹⁴C</formula> respectively. All have 6 protons, but they contain 6, 7, and 8 neutrons respectively.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          Isotopes exhibit nearly identical chemical behavior because chemical properties are determined primarily by the number and arrangement of electrons, which remains the same across isotopes of an element. However, their physical properties can differ significantly due to their mass differences. For instance, heavy water (containing the hydrogen isotope deuterium, <formula type="chemical">²H</formula>) has a higher boiling point than ordinary water.
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          Some isotopes have unstable nuclei that spontaneously emit energy in the form of radiation—a process called radioactivity. These radioactive isotopes gradually transform into different elements through radioactive decay. For example, carbon-14 is radioactive and slowly decays to nitrogen-14. The time it takes for half of a radioactive isotope's atoms to decay is called its half-life, which can range from fractions of a second to billions of years.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Graph showing radioactive decay curve (half-life concept) for Carbon-14. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          Radioactive isotopes have numerous practical applications in medicine, archaeology, agriculture, and industry. In medicine, they're used for diagnosing diseases and treating cancer. In archaeology, carbon-14 dating helps determine the age of organic materials. Industrial applications include testing material strength and finding oil fields.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-av" type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Identical Twins Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Identical Twins Analogy</emphasis>: Imagine isotopes as identical twins who look exactly the same on the outside (same number of protons and electrons) but have different weights (different numbers of neutrons). People interact with them the same way (chemical properties), but they perform differently in activities where weight matters (physical properties).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Dice Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Dice Analogy</emphasis>: Picture isotopes as dice with the same number of dots on the outside (protons and electrons) determining how they interact with other dice (chemical properties), but with different weights inside (neutrons). They roll differently because of their weight differences (physical properties), even though they look identical.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-ex" type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Hydrogen Isotopes">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Hydrogen Isotopes</emphasis>: The simplest element has three isotopes: protium (<formula type="chemical">¹H</formula>, 0 neutrons), deuterium (<formula type="chemical">²H</formula>, 1 neutron), and tritium (<formula type="chemical">³H</formula>, 2 neutrons). While protium and deuterium are stable, tritium is radioactive and decays to helium-3.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Carbon Dating">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Carbon Dating</emphasis>: Carbon-14 is a radioactive isotope formed in the atmosphere that gets incorporated into all living organisms. When an organism dies, it stops taking in carbon-14, and the amount present begins to decrease through radioactive decay with a half-life of about 5,730 years. By measuring the remaining carbon-14 in ancient organic materials, archaeologists can determine their age.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="Medical Applications">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Medical Applications</emphasis>: Technetium-99m is a radioactive isotope widely used in medical imaging. When injected into a patient, it emits gamma rays that can be detected by special cameras, allowing doctors to visualize organs like the brain, heart, or lungs without invasive procedures.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla" type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Medical Diagnosis and Treatment">
          <paragraph>Radioactive isotopes like Iodine-131 are used to diagnose and treat thyroid disorders. Cobalt-60 is used in radiation therapy to destroy cancer cells. Technetium-99m is a common tracer in medical imaging.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Archaeological Dating (Carbon-14 Dating)">
          <paragraph>The decay rate of Carbon-14 is used to determine the age of ancient organic artifacts, such as bones, wood, and cloth, up to about 50,000 years old.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Nuclear Power Generation">
          <paragraph>Isotopes of uranium, particularly Uranium-235, are used as fuel in nuclear power plants to generate electricity through controlled nuclear fission.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Industrial Tracers and Gauges">
          <paragraph>Radioactive isotopes are used as tracers to detect leaks in pipelines, monitor wear in machinery, and gauge the thickness of materials like paper and metal sheets during manufacturing.</paragraph>
        </content>
         <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-rla-item5" type="application_item" title="Smoke Detectors">
          <paragraph>Many common smoke detectors use a small amount of the radioactive isotope Americium-241 to ionize air; smoke particles disrupt this ionization, triggering the alarm.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-ie" type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.3.ie1">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Research Challenge</emphasis>: Investigate how scientists use mass spectrometry to identify and measure the abundance of different isotopes in a sample. How does this technology work, and what can it tell us?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.3.ie2">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Data Analysis</emphasis>: The element chlorine has a relative atomic mass of 35.45, yet no chlorine atom actually has this mass. Research the natural abundances of chlorine isotopes and calculate how this average mass comes about.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.3.ie3">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Experiment Design</emphasis>: If you were a nuclear scientist working with radioactive isotopes, what safety protocols would you need to implement? Research and create a safety checklist.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="2.3.ie4">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Ethical Question</emphasis>: Nuclear medicine uses radioactive isotopes to diagnose and treat diseases, including cancer. Research and debate the benefits versus risks of using these materials in medical treatments.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-kps" type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Isotopes are atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons.</point>
          <point>All isotopes of an element have identical chemical properties because they have the same electron configuration.</point>
          <point>Physical properties of isotopes differ due to their different masses.</point>
          <point>Radioactive isotopes have unstable nuclei that emit radiation and transform into other elements.</point>
          <point>Applications of radioactive isotopes include medical imaging, cancer treatment, archaeological dating, industrial testing, and generating nuclear power.</point>
          <point>Ionizing radiation from radioactive sources can remove electrons from atoms, creating ions.</point>
          <point>Carbon-14 dating uses the predictable decay of a radioactive carbon isotope to determine the age of organic materials.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exc" type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch2-topic2.3-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
