    <topic id="ch3-topic3.6" title="Compare the Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Ionic and covalent compounds represent fundamentally different types of chemical bonding, with ionic compounds formed through electron transfer between metals and non-metals creating charged particles, while covalent compounds form through electron sharing between non-metals, resulting in distinct physical and chemical properties.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Side-by-side comparison: Ionic compound (e.g., NaCl lattice structure) vs. Covalent compound (e.g., discrete H2O molecules). Highlight electron transfer vs. sharing. - necessity_score: 10/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          Ionic and covalent compounds differ dramatically in their formation, structure, and resulting properties. Ionic compounds form when a metal transfers electrons to a non-metal, creating oppositely charged ions that attract each other through strong electrostatic forces. These forces arrange the ions into a rigid, three-dimensional crystalline lattice structure where each ion is surrounded by ions of opposite charge. This arrangement gives ionic compounds their characteristic high melting and boiling points.
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          Covalent compounds, by contrast, form when two or more non-metals share electrons rather than transferring them completely. This sharing creates discrete molecules that maintain their individual identity rather than forming extended lattices. The shared electrons create a strong bond between the atoms within each molecule, but the forces between separate molecules (intermolecular forces) are typically much weaker than the ionic forces in ionic compounds.
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          The differences in bonding and structure explain why ionic compounds exist as high-melting solids at room temperature, while many covalent compounds exist as gases or liquids. The strong electrostatic forces in ionic compounds require significant energy to overcome, while the weaker intermolecular forces between covalent molecules can be disrupted much more easily. These fundamental differences also explain their behavior in solvents, electrical conductivity, and many other physical properties.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies &amp; Visualizations">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Handshake vs. Magnet Analogy">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Handshake vs. Magnet Analogy</emphasis>: Covalent bonds are like two people holding hands (sharing electrons), creating distinct pairs that can move around independently. Ionic bonds are like magnets that attract each other from all directions, creating large organized structures where each piece is attracted to multiple surrounding pieces.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Two people shaking hands (covalent) vs. multiple magnets attracting each other to form a lattice (ionic). - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Library vs. Concert Crowd">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Library vs. Concert Crowd</emphasis>: An ionic compound is like an organized library where each book (ion) has its specific place on the shelf, creating a stable, rigid structure. A covalent compound is more like concert attendees, where small groups (molecules) form but move independently of other groups, with much looser organization between the separate groups.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Sodium Chloride (NaCl) - A classic ionic compound">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Sodium Chloride (NaCl) - A classic ionic compound</emphasis>: Sodium (Na) transfers its outer electron to chlorine (Cl), forming <formula type="chemical">Na⁺</formula> and <formula type="chemical">Cl⁻</formula> ions that arrange in a cubic lattice. This ionic structure gives table salt its high melting point (801°C), crystal structure, water solubility, and ability to conduct electricity when molten or dissolved.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Water (H₂O) - A polar covalent compound">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>) - A polar covalent compound</emphasis>: Oxygen shares electrons with two hydrogen atoms, but pulls the shared electrons closer to itself due to higher electronegativity. This creates a bent molecule with partial charges, allowing for hydrogen bonding between molecules. These hydrogen bonds give water higher melting and boiling points than would be expected for a molecule of its size.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="Methane (CH₄) - A nonpolar covalent compound">
          <paragraph><emphasis type="bold">Methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>) - A nonpolar covalent compound</emphasis>: Carbon shares electrons equally with four hydrogen atoms, creating a symmetrical tetrahedral molecule with no partial charges. Without strong intermolecular forces, methane exists as a gas at room temperature, has a very low boiling point, and is insoluble in water.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Ionic Compounds in Electrolytes">
          <paragraph>Ionic compounds like salts (e.g., NaCl, KCl) dissolve in water to form electrolyte solutions that conduct electricity. This property is vital for nerve function in biological systems and in batteries.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Covalent Compounds as Fuels">
          <paragraph>Many covalent compounds, especially hydrocarbons like methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>), propane (<formula type="chemical">C₃H₈</formula>), and octane (<formula type="chemical">C₈H₁₈</formula>), are excellent fuels because their C-H and C-C bonds store significant energy released upon combustion.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Solubility Differences in Cleaning">
          <paragraph>The "like dissolves like" principle, based on bond polarity, is used in cleaning. Water (polar covalent) dissolves ionic dirt and polar covalent stains, while non-polar solvents (covalent) are needed for grease and oil (non-polar covalent).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Materials Hardness and Softness">
          <paragraph>Ionic compounds form hard, brittle crystals (e.g., ceramics). Many covalent compounds form softer materials (e.g., wax, plastics), though network covalent solids like diamond are extremely hard. These differences are due to bond strength and structure.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-ie-list" type="interactive_prompt_list">
          <interactive_prompt id="3.6.ie1">
