            <paragraph>5. Design an experiment that would allow you to determine whether an unknown white crystalline substance is ionic or covalent based on its properties.</paragraph>
          </interactive_prompt>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Ionic compounds form through electron transfer between metals and non-metals, creating charged ions held together by electrostatic forces.</point>
          <point>Covalent compounds form through electron sharing between non-metals, creating discrete neutral molecules.</point>
          <point>Ionic compounds typically have high melting and boiling points due to strong electrostatic forces throughout their crystal lattice.</point>
          <point>Covalent compounds generally have lower melting and boiling points because of weaker intermolecular forces.</point>
          <point>Ionic compounds dissolve well in polar solvents like water but not in non-polar solvents.</point>
          <point>Covalent compounds typically dissolve in non-polar solvents like ether and benzene but not in water (unless they are polar covalent, like sugar or alcohol).</point>
          <point>Ionic compounds conduct electricity when molten or in solution due to mobile ions, while most covalent compounds do not conduct electricity.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.6-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="3.6.ex1" level="basic"> <!-- Changed from general to basic -->
            <question><paragraph>1. A compound has a melting point of 812°C, dissolves in water, and conducts electricity when dissolved. Is it more likely to be ionic or covalent? Explain your reasoning.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Ionic, because the high melting point, water solubility, and electrical conductivity in solution are characteristic properties of ionic compounds.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.6.ex2" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>2. Explain why sodium chloride (NaCl) has a much higher melting point (801°C) than chlorine gas (<formula type="chemical">Cl₂</formula>, melting point -101.5°C), even though both contain chlorine.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: NaCl has strong electrostatic forces between oppositely charged ions throughout its crystal lattice, requiring significant energy to overcome. <formula type="chemical">Cl₂</formula> consists of discrete molecules with only weak van der Waals forces (London dispersion forces) between them, which are easily overcome.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.6.ex3" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>3. Draw the electron dot structure for carbon dioxide and predict whether it would dissolve better in water or hexane. Explain your reasoning.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: O=C=O (linear molecule with two double bonds). <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> would dissolve better in hexane. Although C=O bonds are polar, the linear symmetry of the molecule makes <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> overall non-polar. It follows the "like dissolves like" principle, dissolving better in non-polar hexane than in polar water.</paragraph></answer>
