      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.7-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Intermolecular forces are attractions between molecules that are weaker than chemical bonds but determine physical properties.</point>
          <point>The strength of intermolecular forces increases from gases (weakest) to liquids to solids (strongest).</point>
          <point>Stronger intermolecular forces result in higher melting and boiling points.</point>
          <point>Dipole-dipole forces occur between polar molecules due to partial charge attractions.</point>
          <point>Hydrogen bonding is a special case of dipole-dipole forces that occurs when hydrogen is bonded to highly electronegative elements (F, O, N).</point>
          <point>Hydrogen bonding is responsible for water's unusually high melting and boiling points compared to similar compounds.</point>
          <point>The physical state of a substance at room temperature is determined by the balance between molecular kinetic energy and intermolecular force strength.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.7-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="3.7.ex1" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>1. Water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>) has a boiling point of 100°C, while methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>) has a boiling point of -161.5°C, even though methane has a similar molecular mass. Explain this difference based on intermolecular forces.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: Water molecules form strong hydrogen bonds with each other. Methane is a non-polar molecule and only interacts through very weak London dispersion forces. The hydrogen bonds in water require much more energy (higher temperature) to overcome than the weak forces in methane.</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.7.ex2" level="basic"> <!-- Changed from general to basic -->
            <question><paragraph>2. Draw diagrams showing how HCl molecules would arrange themselves due to dipole-dipole forces and how water molecules would arrange themselves due to hydrogen bonding.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: For HCl, draw molecules aligned with the H (δ+) of one molecule pointing toward the Cl (δ-) of another. For water, draw networks where the H atoms (δ+) of one water molecule point toward the O atoms (δ-) of adjacent molecules, forming hydrogen bonds.</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.7.ex3" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>3. Arrange the following compounds in order of increasing boiling point: <formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>, <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>, <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>. Explain your reasoning.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: CH₄ &lt; NH₃ &lt; H₂O. Methane (nonpolar) has only weak London dispersion forces. Ammonia (<formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>) has hydrogen bonding (N-H). Water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>) also has hydrogen bonding (O-H), but oxygen is more electronegative than nitrogen, and each water molecule can participate in up to four hydrogen bonds, making water's hydrogen bonding network stronger than ammonia's. This results in the observed order of boiling points.</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.7.ex4" level="basic"> <!-- Changed from general to basic -->
            <question><paragraph>4. If the electronegativity of hydrogen is 2.20 and that of chlorine is 3.16, calculate the electronegativity difference and explain why this creates a polar bond in HCl.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: Electronegativity difference = 3.16 - 2.20 = 0.96. This significant difference causes unequal electron sharing, with chlorine pulling the shared electrons more strongly than hydrogen. This creates a partial negative charge on Cl and a partial positive charge on H, resulting in a polar bond.</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="3.7.ex5" level="advanced"> <!-- Changed from general to advanced -->
            <question><paragraph>5. Explain why hydrogen bonding only occurs with F, O, and N bonded to hydrogen, but not with other elements like chlorine (which is also quite electronegative).</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer: Hydrogen bonding requires a hydrogen atom bonded to a small, highly electronegative atom (F, O, or N) and a lone pair of electrons on another F, O, or N atom. Fluorine, oxygen, and nitrogen meet these criteria: they are highly electronegative, creating a very polar H-X bond, and they are small, allowing the lone pair on an adjacent molecule to approach the H closely. Chlorine, while electronegative, is larger, and its H-Cl bond is less polar than H-F, H-O, or H-N, resulting in weaker dipole-dipole forces rather than true hydrogen bonds.</emphasis></paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch3-topic3.7-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="States of Matter">
          <paragraph>Intermolecular forces directly determine the state of matter (solid, liquid, gas) of a substance at a given temperature by influencing how strongly molecules are held together.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.7-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Solutions and Solubility">
          <paragraph>The principle "like dissolves like" is based on intermolecular forces - polar substances with dipole-dipole forces or hydrogen bonding dissolve well in polar solvents, while non-polar substances dissolve in non-polar solvents.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch3-topic3.7-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Biological Systems">
          <paragraph>Hydrogen bonding is crucial in biological systems, determining the structure of proteins (secondary structure like alpha-helices and beta-sheets), DNA double helix formation, and many other essential biochemical processes.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts &amp; Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="3.7.ff1"><paragraph>1. Without hydrogen bonding, water would be a gas at room temperature like <formula type="chemical">H₂S</formula>, making life as we know it impossible. This demonstrates how dramatically intermolecular forces can affect a substance's properties.</paragraph></content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="3.7.ff2"><paragraph>2. Ice floats on water because hydrogen bonds in ice create a crystalline structure that is less dense than liquid water - a rare property that has profound implications for aquatic life, which can survive under frozen lakes and oceans.</paragraph></content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="3.7.ff3"><paragraph>3. The "stickiness" of water that allows insects like water striders to walk on its surface (surface tension) is a direct result of hydrogen bonding between water molecules at the surface, which creates a sort of invisible "skin" on the water.</paragraph></content>
      </section>
