        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-ex-item4" type="example_item" title="Ionic Compound Formula: Potassium bromide (KBr)">
          <paragraph>Potassium bromide (KBr): One potassium ion (<formula type="chemical">K⁺</formula>) combined with one bromide ion (<formula type="chemical">Br⁻</formula>)</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-ex-item5" type="example_item" title="Covalent Compound Formula: Water (H₂O)">
          <paragraph>Covalent Compound Formulas: Water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>): Two hydrogen atoms bonded to one oxygen atom</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-ex-item6" type="example_item" title="Covalent Compound Formula: Hydrogen peroxide (H₂O₂)">
          <paragraph>Hydrogen peroxide (<formula type="chemical">H₂O₂</formula>): Two hydrogen atoms bonded to two oxygen atoms</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-ex-item7" type="example_item" title="Covalent Compound Formula: Methane (CH₄)">
          <paragraph>Methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>): One carbon atom bonded to four hydrogen atoms</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Pharmaceuticals">
          <paragraph>The chemical formula of a drug (e.g., Aspirin: <formula type="chemical">C₉H₈O₄</formula>) precisely defines its composition, which is critical for its synthesis, dosage, and therapeutic effect.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Food Additives and Nutrition">
          <paragraph>Chemical formulas are used to identify food additives (e.g., Sodium Benzoate: <formula type="chemical">C₇H₅NaO₂</formula>) and nutrients (e.g., Glucose: <formula type="chemical">C₆H₁₂O₆</formula>), ensuring correct formulation and labeling.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Industrial Chemicals">
          <paragraph>Manufacturing processes rely on chemical formulas to produce vast quantities of materials like sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>) for batteries and fertilizers, or ammonia (<formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>) for cleaning products and fertilizers.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.1-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Material Science">
          <paragraph>The formula of a material, like silicon dioxide (<formula type="chemical">SiO₂</formula>) for glass or polyethylene (<formula type="chemical">(C₂H₄)ₙ</formula>) for plastics, dictates its properties and applications.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
