    <topic id="ch4-topic4.4" title="Chemical Formulas of Compounds">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          The molecular formula of a compound shows the actual number and types of atoms present in one molecule, and can be determined from its empirical formula and molar mass through the relationship: Molecular formula = n × (Empirical Formula), where n is the ratio of molar mass to empirical formula mass.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Flowchart: Elemental Analysis -> % Composition -> Empirical Formula -(Molar Mass)-> Molecular Formula. - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          To find a compound's molecular formula, we must first determine its empirical formula, which shows the simplest whole-number ratio of atoms. This is typically done using experimental data on the mass percent composition of the compound. While the empirical formula gives us the basic ratio of atoms, it doesn't tell us the actual number of atoms in a molecule.
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          The relationship between molecular and empirical formulas is expressed by: Molecular formula = n × (Empirical Formula), where n is a whole number determined by dividing the compound's molar mass by its empirical formula mass. This n value tells us how many empirical formula units make up one molecule.
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          For example, hydrogen peroxide has an empirical formula of HO with an empirical formula mass of approximately 17 g/mol. Since its molar mass is approximately 34 g/mol, we calculate n = 34 ÷ 17 = 2. Therefore, its molecular formula is <formula type="chemical">(HO)₂</formula> = <formula type="chemical">H₂O₂</formula>, showing that one molecule contains two hydrogen atoms and two oxygen atoms.
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          When n equals 1, the molecular formula is identical to the empirical formula, as is the case with water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>). However, many compounds have molecular formulas that are multiples of their empirical formulas, providing critical information about their true molecular structure and properties.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies &amp; Visualizations">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Train Car Analogy">
          <paragraph>Think of an empirical formula as a single train car with a specific ratio of passengers (atoms). The molecular formula tells you how many identical cars make up the complete train. If each car (empirical unit) has 1 adult and 2 children (representing <formula type="chemical">CH₂</formula>), and the full train (molecule) has 6 adults and 12 children, the molecular formula would be <formula type="chemical">C₆H₁₂</formula>, and n would be 6.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: A single train car labeled "CH₂" (Empirical). Then, a train of 6 such cars labeled "C₆H₁₂" (Molecular). - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Building Block Analogy">
          <paragraph>Imagine the empirical formula as a basic building block like a brick. The molecular formula tells you how many of these identical bricks are cemented together to make the complete molecular structure. If glucose has an empirical formula of <formula type="chemical">CH₂O</formula> but a molecular formula of <formula type="chemical">C₆H₁₂O₆</formula>, it means six empirical "bricks" are joined together.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Hydrogen Peroxide">
          <paragraph>Hydrogen Peroxide:</paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Empirical formula: HO</item>
            <item>Empirical formula mass: 1.01 g/mol (H) + 16.00 g/mol (O) = 17.01 g/mol</item>
            <item>Molar mass: 34.02 g/mol</item>
            <item>n = Molar mass / Empirical formula mass = 34.02 g/mol ÷ 17.01 g/mol ≈ 2</item>
            <item>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">(HO)₂</formula> = <formula type="chemical">H₂O₂</formula></item>
          </list>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Benzene">
          <paragraph>Benzene:</paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Empirical formula: CH</item>
            <item>Empirical formula mass: 12.01 g/mol (C) + 1.01 g/mol (H) = 13.02 g/mol</item>
            <item>Molar mass: 78.12 g/mol</item>
            <item>n = 78.12 g/mol ÷ 13.02 g/mol ≈ 6</item>
            <item>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">(CH)₆</formula> = <formula type="chemical">C₆H₆</formula></item>
          </list>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="Glucose">
          <paragraph>Glucose:</paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Empirical formula: <formula type="chemical">CH₂O</formula></item>
            <item>Empirical formula mass: 12.01 (C) + 2(1.01) (H) + 16.00 (O) = 30.03 g/mol</item>
            <item>Molar mass: 180.18 g/mol</item>
            <item>n = 180.18 g/mol ÷ 30.03 g/mol ≈ 6</item>
            <item>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">(CH₂O)₆</formula> = <formula type="chemical">C₆H₁₂O₆</formula></item>
          </list>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Identifying Unknown Compounds">
          <paragraph>In chemical research and forensics, determining the molecular formula is crucial for identifying unknown substances. Elemental analysis gives the empirical formula, and mass spectrometry provides the molar mass, together revealing the molecular formula.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Drug Development">
          <paragraph>The exact molecular formula of a drug is essential for understanding its structure, how it interacts with biological targets, and for ensuring correct dosage and purity in manufacturing.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Understanding Polymer Structure">
          <paragraph>While polymers are very large molecules, the concept of a repeating empirical unit (monomer) is central to understanding their structure and properties. The overall molecular formula of a polymer is effectively (Empirical Monomer Formula)ₙ, where n is very large.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="4.4.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. A compound has an empirical formula of <formula type="chemical">C₂H₅O</formula> and a molar mass of approximately 90 g/mol. Try calculating its molecular formula. What common household substance might this be? (Hint: Consider diethyl ether or isomers of butanol).</paragraph>
        </content>
