        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>The molecular formula shows the actual number of atoms in one molecule of a compound.</point>
          <point>The empirical formula shows only the simplest whole-number ratio of atoms.</point>
          <point>Molecular formula = n × (Empirical Formula), where n is a whole number.</point>
          <point>n is calculated by dividing the molar mass by the empirical formula mass.</point>
          <point>When n = 1, the molecular and empirical formulas are identical.</point>
          <point>Determining the molecular formula requires both the empirical formula (from % composition) and the molar mass (e.g., from mass spectrometry).</point>
          <point>The molecular formula provides more complete information about a compound's composition than the empirical formula alone.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
