      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Organic Chemistry">
          <paragraph>Molecular formulas are essential in organic chemistry for identifying compounds and their structural isomers.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Chemical Analysis">
          <paragraph>Determining molecular formulas connects to analytical techniques like mass spectrometry (for molar mass) and elemental analysis (for empirical formula).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.4-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Biochemistry">
          <paragraph>Many biomolecules like glucose (<formula type="chemical">C₆H₁₂O₆</formula>) have molecular formulas that are multiples of their empirical formulas (<formula type="chemical">CH₂O</formula>), showing the importance of this concept in biological systems.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts &amp; Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.4.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Caffeine has the molecular formula <formula type="chemical">C₈H₁₀N₄O₂</formula> - containing 24 atoms in total, which is significantly more complex than its empirical formula of <formula type="chemical">C₄H₅N₂O</formula>!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.4.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) has the molecular formula <formula type="chemical">C₆H₈O₆</formula>. Its empirical formula is <formula type="chemical">C₃H₄O₃</formula> (n=2).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.4.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. The structural formula can reveal important information that the molecular formula doesn't show - for example, ethanol (<formula type="chemical">C₂H₆O</formula>) and dimethyl ether (<formula type="chemical">C₂H₆O</formula>) have identical molecular formulas but different structures and properties (they are isomers).</paragraph>
        </content>
