    <topic id="ch4-topic4.5" title="Deduce the Molecular Formula from the Structural Formula">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Deducing the molecular formula from a structural formula involves identifying and counting all atoms present in the structural representation to determine the total number of each element type in the molecule.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: A structural formula (e.g., ethanol CH₃CH₂OH) with each atom type (C, H, O) highlighted and counted to arrive at the molecular formula C₂H₆O. - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          The structural formula of a compound shows how atoms are arranged and bonded to each other in a molecule, providing a visual representation of its structure. From this detailed structural information, we can determine the molecular formula by following a simple step-by-step process.
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          First, we examine the structural formula of the compound, which shows the arrangement of atoms and bonds. Next, we carefully count the number of atoms of each element present in the structure. Then, we write the symbols of all elements found in the compound (usually C first, then H, then others alphabetically). Following this, we add subscripts indicating the total number of atoms for each element type. Finally, we remove any subscript "1" since it's understood that a single atom is present when no subscript is shown.
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          For example, with sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>), the structural formula shows two hydrogen atoms, one sulfur atom, and four oxygen atoms arranged in a specific configuration. Counting these atoms and writing the symbols with appropriate subscripts gives us the molecular formula <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>. This approach allows us to translate the detailed structural information into the more compact molecular formula notation.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies &amp; Visualizations">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="Blueprint to Materials List Analogy">
          <paragraph>Think of a structural formula as a detailed architectural blueprint showing the layout and connections of a house, while the molecular formula is like the simplified materials list that just tells you how many of each component (2 doors, 6 windows, 1 roof) you need without showing their arrangement.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="Recipe Analogy">
          <paragraph>If the structural formula is like a cooking procedure showing how ingredients are combined step by step, the molecular formula is like the ingredients list that simply states "2 eggs, 1 cup flour, 3 tablespoons sugar" without indicating how they're mixed together.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Sulfuric Acid">
          <paragraph>Sulfuric Acid:</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Structural formula:</paragraph>
          <paragraph><pre>  O
  ‖
H-O-S-O-H
  ‖
  O</pre></paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: The structural formula of Sulfuric Acid as shown. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
          <paragraph>Counting atoms: 2 H atoms, 1 S atom, 4 O atoms</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula></paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Phosphoric Acid">
