HO-P=O
  |
  OH</pre></paragraph> <!-- Corrected structural formula for H3PO4 -->
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: The structural formula of Phosphoric Acid as shown (corrected). - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
          <paragraph>Counting atoms: 3 H atoms, 1 P atom, 4 O atoms</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">H₃PO₄</formula></paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-ex-item3" type="example_item" title="n-Propyl Alcohol">
          <paragraph>n-Propyl Alcohol (Propan-1-ol):</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Structural formula: <formula type="chemical">CH₃-CH₂-CH₂-OH</formula></paragraph>
          <paragraph>Counting atoms: 3 C atoms, 8 H atoms (3+2+2+1), 1 O atom</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Molecular formula: <formula type="chemical">C₃H₈O</formula></paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Drug Discovery and Design">
          <paragraph>Chemists often work with structural formulas to understand how a drug molecule might fit into a biological target (like an enzyme or receptor). Deducing the molecular formula from these structures helps in calculating molar mass for dosage and in patenting new compounds.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Understanding Isomers">
          <paragraph>Compounds can have the same molecular formula but different structural formulas (isomers), leading to different properties. Deducing the molecular formula from various structural isomers helps confirm they share the same atomic composition despite different arrangements (e.g., propan-1-ol and propan-2-ol both have molecular formula <formula type="chemical">C₃H₈O</formula>).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Chemical Databases and Literature">
          <paragraph>Chemical literature and databases often present compounds as structural formulas. Scientists deduce molecular formulas from these to quickly assess composition, calculate molar mass, or search for related compounds based on atomic counts.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="4.5.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. Draw the structural formula for ethanol (<formula type="chemical">CH₃CH₂OH</formula>) and verify you can count the atoms correctly to get the molecular formula <formula type="chemical">C₂H₆O</formula>.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="4.5.ie2">
          <paragraph>2. Research the structural formula of aspirin (<emphasis type="italic">acetylsalicylic acid</emphasis>) and try to deduce its molecular formula by counting the atoms. Then verify your answer online.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="4.5.ie3">
          <paragraph>3. How would the structural and molecular formulas differ for isomers like butane (<formula type="chemical">CH₃CH₂CH₂CH₃</formula>) and isobutane (<formula type="chemical">CH₃CH(CH₃)CH₃</formula>)? Why is the structural formula more informative in this case?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="4.5.ie4">
          <paragraph>4. If you're given the structural formula for glucose (which contains a ring structure), what challenges might you face in counting atoms compared to a simpler linear molecule?</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.5-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>The structural formula shows the arrangement and bonding of atoms in a molecule.</point>
          <point>To deduce the molecular formula, count all atoms of each element in the structural formula.</point>
          <point>Write element symbols (C first, then H, then alphabetically) followed by subscripts indicating the total number of each atom type.</point>
          <point>Remove any subscript "1" as it's implied when no subscript is shown.</point>
          <point>The molecular formula provides composition information but not structural arrangement.</point>
          <point>Different compounds can have the same molecular formula but different structural formulas (isomers).</point>
          <point>Structural formulas provide more detailed information about molecular structure than molecular formulas.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
