          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.6-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Stoichiometry">
          <paragraph>Avogadro's number is crucial for stoichiometric calculations, allowing chemists to predict the exact quantities of reactants needed and products formed in chemical reactions based on particle counts.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.6-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Gas Laws">
          <paragraph>In the study of gases, one mole of any gas at standard temperature and pressure occupies approximately 22.4 liters—a concept directly related to Avogadro's number and Avogadro's Law.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.6-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Atomic Theory">
          <paragraph>Avogadro's number bridges the theoretical models of atomic structure with experimental measurements, validating our understanding of matter's particulate nature.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts &amp; Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.6.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. If you had Avogadro's number of standard playing cards and stacked them on top of each other, the stack would reach from Earth to the sun and back over 6 million times!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.6.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. The determination of Avogadro's number was a challenging scientific problem that took over a century to solve precisely. Modern measurements use techniques including X-ray crystallography and electrolysis.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="4.6.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. In 2019, scientists officially redefined the mole in terms of exactly <formula type="math">6.02214076 × 10²³</formula> elementary entities, making Avogadro's number an exact defined constant rather than an experimentally determined one.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
