          <paragraph>4. Create a visual representation of one mole of different substances. How would their volumes compare? Consider examples like hydrogen gas (at STP), iron metal, water, and table sugar.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.7-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>One mole contains exactly <formula type="math">6.02214076 × 10²³</formula> particles (Avogadro's number).</point>
          <point>The mole is a counting unit, similar to a dozen but much larger.</point>
          <point>Molar mass is the mass of one mole of a substance in grams (g/mol).</point>
          <point>Molar mass is numerically equal to atomic/molecular/formula mass in atomic mass units (amu).</point>
          <point>Different substances have different molar masses but the same number of particles per mole.</point>
          <point>The mole concept allows chemists to convert between number of particles and measurable mass.</point>
          <point>Molar mass is calculated by adding the atomic masses of all atoms in a chemical formula.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
