      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.7-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Chemical Reactions">
          <paragraph>The mole concept is essential for balancing chemical equations and predicting the quantities of products formed in reactions. Chemists use molar ratios to determine the amounts of reactants needed.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.7-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Gas Laws">
          <paragraph>One mole of any ideal gas at standard temperature and pressure (STP) occupies 22.4 liters, allowing for convenient conversions between volume and amount in gas calculations.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch4-topic4.7-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Solutions">
          <paragraph>Solution concentrations like molarity (moles per liter) rely on the mole concept, enabling precise preparation of solutions for laboratory and industrial applications.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts &amp; Trivia">
