        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points &amp; Summary">
        <content id="ch4-topic4.8-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Chemical equations represent reactions using chemical formulas and symbols.</point>
          <point>The law of conservation of mass requires that chemical equations be balanced (same number of each atom type on both sides).</point>
          <point>Reactants appear on the left side of the equation; products on the right, separated by an arrow (→ or ⇌).</point>
          <point>Physical states are indicated by (s) for solid, (l) for liquid, (g) for gas, and (aq) for aqueous solution.</point>
          <point>A properly written chemical equation shows the correct formulas of all substances.</point>
          <point>Chemical equations show the mole ratios between reactants and products.</point>
          <point>Reversible reactions use double arrows (⇌) to show that the reaction proceeds in both directions.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
