  <chapter id="ch5" title="Energetics">
    <topic id="ch5-topic5.1" title="Chemical Systems and Surroundings">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          A chemical system is any physical or chemical change under study, while everything else that doesn't fall within this system is called the surrounding. Energy transfer between these two components determines whether a reaction is exothermic (energy flows from system to surroundings) or endothermic (energy flows from surroundings to system).
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Diagram showing a beaker (system) with arrows indicating heat flow to surroundings (exothermic, beaker feels hot) and another beaker with arrows indicating heat flow from surroundings (endothermic, beaker feels cold). - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          Chemical reactions involve energy transfers that are fundamental to understanding how reactions work. When studying any chemical reaction, we define boundaries: the reaction itself (including reactants, products, catalysts, and solvents) forms the "system," while everything else constitutes the "surroundings."
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          This distinction helps us track energy flow during reactions. When a system releases energy to its surroundings (like heat being released during combustion), we call this an exothermic reaction and mark it with a negative sign for enthalpy change (ΔH). The surroundings become warmer as they gain energy from the system. Conversely, when a system absorbs energy from its surroundings (like water absorbing heat when boiling), we call this an endothermic reaction and mark it with a positive sign for enthalpy change (ΔH). The surroundings become cooler as they lose energy to the system.
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          Understanding these energy transfers helps us predict how reactions will behave and how we might harness them for practical purposes. For instance, exothermic reactions can be used for heating, while endothermic reactions can be used for cooling applications.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Campfire Analogy">
          <paragraph>Think of an exothermic reaction as a campfire. The burning wood (system) releases heat to the surrounding air and people (surroundings), making them warmer. People sitting around the fire can feel the heat coming from the system to the surroundings.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Simple animation of a campfire with heat radiating outwards to people. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="The Ice Pack Analogy">
          <paragraph>An endothermic reaction is like a chemical ice pack used for injuries. When you squeeze the pack, chemicals inside mix and absorb heat from your skin (surroundings), making the surrounding area cooler. The system (chemicals) is taking energy from your skin, causing the cooling effect.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Animation of an instant cold pack getting cold, with arrows showing heat moving from the surroundings (e.g., a hand) into the pack. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Exothermic Example: Hydrogen and Oxygen Reaction">
          <paragraph>When hydrogen gas reacts with oxygen gas to form water, heat is released:</paragraph>
          <paragraph><formula type="chemical">2H₂(g) + O₂(g) → 2H₂O(l) + 571.6 kJ</formula></paragraph>
          <paragraph>This reaction powers rocket engines and is highly exothermic, releasing 571.6 kJ of energy per 2 moles of water formed.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Endothermic Example: Hydrogen and Iodine Reaction">
          <paragraph>When solid iodine reacts with hydrogen gas to form hydrogen iodide, heat is absorbed:</paragraph>
          <paragraph><formula type="chemical">H₂(g) + I₂(s) → 2HI(g) - 53.08 kJ</formula> (or ΔH = +53.08 kJ)</paragraph>
          <paragraph>This reaction only occurs at high temperatures because it needs to absorb energy from the surroundings to proceed.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Hand Warmers (Exothermic)">
          <paragraph>Disposable hand warmers utilize exothermic reactions, often the oxidation of iron powder, to release heat and provide warmth in cold conditions. The system (chemicals inside) releases energy to the surroundings (your hands).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Instant Cold Packs (Endothermic)">
          <paragraph>Instant cold packs used for sports injuries contain chemicals (e.g., ammonium nitrate and water) that undergo an endothermic reaction when mixed. They absorb heat from the surroundings (the injured area), causing a cooling effect.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Combustion for Energy (Exothermic)">
          <paragraph>Burning fuels like natural gas, wood, or gasoline are exothermic reactions. The heat released is used for cooking, heating homes, generating electricity, and powering vehicles.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.1-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Photosynthesis (Endothermic)">
          <paragraph>Plants use photosynthesis to convert carbon dioxide and water into glucose and oxygen. This process is endothermic, as it absorbs energy from sunlight to drive the chemical reactions.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="5.1.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. Imagine you're holding a self-heating coffee cup that uses an exothermic reaction. What happens to your hand as the reaction proceeds? Can you explain the energy flow in terms of system and surroundings?</paragraph>
        </content>
