            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Vaporization requires more energy. Melting involves overcoming some intermolecular forces to allow molecules to move from fixed positions to a more mobile liquid state. Vaporization requires overcoming nearly all intermolecular forces to separate liquid molecules into widely dispersed gas molecules, which needs significantly more energy.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch5-topic5.2-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Thermochemistry">
          <paragraph>Enthalpy is a key concept in thermochemistry, which studies heat flow in different types of reactions, including combustion, neutralization, and phase changes.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.2-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Hess's Law">
          <paragraph>This principle allows chemists to calculate enthalpy changes for reactions that are difficult to measure directly by adding enthalpy changes of related, known reactions.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch5-topic5.2-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Bond Energies">
          <paragraph>The enthalpy change in reactions can be estimated from bond energies (energy required to break bonds minus energy released when bonds form), connecting enthalpy to molecular structure and bonding.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="5.2.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. The largest exothermic reaction ever caused by humans was the Tsar Bomba nuclear test, which released energy equivalent to about 50 megatons of TNT or <formula type="math">2.1 × 10¹⁷</formula> joules!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="5.2.ff2">
