      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch6-topic6.2-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Chemical Kinetics">
          <paragraph>Dynamic equilibrium bridges thermodynamics (which tells us where a reaction wants to go in terms of energy and stability) with kinetics (how fast it gets there). The equilibrium constant (K) quantifies how far a reaction proceeds before reaching dynamic equilibrium.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch6-topic6.2-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Phase Equilibria">
          <paragraph>The principles of dynamic equilibrium apply not just to chemical reactions but also to physical processes like evaporation/condensation (liquid-gas equilibrium) or melting/freezing (solid-liquid equilibrium).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
