        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch6-topic6.3-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Le Châtelier's Principle: A system at equilibrium responds to disturbances by shifting to minimize the effect of the disturbance.</point>
          <point>Concentration: Adding a substance shifts equilibrium away from it; removing shifts toward it.</point>
          <point>Temperature: For exothermic reactions, ↑T shifts left, ↓T shifts right. For endothermic, ↑T shifts right, ↓T shifts left.</point>
          <point>Pressure (gases): ↑P shifts to side with fewer gas moles; ↓P shifts to side with more gas moles. No effect if gas moles are equal.</point>
          <point>Catalyst: Speeds up reaching equilibrium but does not change equilibrium position.</point>
          <point>Continuous removal of products can drive reversible reactions to completion.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
