                <item>(c) The concentrations of all the reactants and the products should become constant.</item>
                <item>(d) One of the products should be removed from the reaction mixture.</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (c)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex6" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>6. Why does gas start coming out when you open a can of fizzy drink?</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>(a) Because the solubility of the gas increases</item>
                <item>(b) Because the gas is insoluble in water</item>
                <item>(c) Because the gas is dissolved under pressure hence it comes out when pressure is decreased</item>
                <item>(d) Because the solubility of the gas decreases at high pressure</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (c)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex7" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph>7. The following reaction is performed in a closed vessel: <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃(s) ⇌ CaO(s) + CO₂(g)</formula>. How will the equilibrium be affected if you increase the pressure (by decreasing volume)?</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>(a) The forward reaction will be favoured</item>
                <item>(b) The backward reaction will be favoured</item>
                <item>(c) No effect on backward reaction</item>
                <item>(d) No effect on forward or backward reaction</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (b)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex8" level="advanced">
            <question><paragraph>8. When will a reaction become a reversible one (in terms of activation energy)?</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>(a) If the activation energy of the forward reaction is comparable to that of backward reaction</item>
                <item>(b) If the activation energy of the forward reaction is higher than that of backward reaction</item>
                <item>(c) If the activation energy of the forward reaction is lower than that of backward reaction</item>
                <item>(d) If the enthalpy change of both the reactions is zero.</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (a) (If both activation energies are surmountable under the given conditions.)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex9" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph>9. Is a reversible reaction useful for preparing compounds on large scale?</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>(a) No</item>
                <item>(b) Yes</item>
                <item>(c) They are useful only when equilibrium lies far to the right side or can be shifted there.</item>
                <item>(d) They are useful only when equilibrium lies far to the left side.</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (c)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex10" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>10. What will happen to the concentrations of the products if a reversible reaction at equilibrium is not disturbed?</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>(a) They will remain constant</item>
                <item>(b) They will keep on increasing</item>
                <item>(c) They will keep on decreasing</item>
                <item>(d) They will remain constant for some time and then start decreasing</item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: (a)</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex11" level="intermediate" title="Short Answer Questions">
              <question>
                  <paragraph>i. How is dynamic equilibrium different from static equilibrium?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>ii. How will the following reversible reaction be affected if its temperature is increased? <formula type="chemical">2H₂O(l) + Electricity ⇌ 2H₂(g) + O₂(g)</formula> (Assume electricity provides energy, making it endothermic overall)</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>iii. How can you get the maximum yield in a reversible reaction?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>iv. How can you decrease the time to attain the position of equilibrium in a reversible reaction?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>v. What is the effect of increasing pressure on the following reaction at equilibrium? <formula type="chemical">N₂(g) + O₂(g) ⇌ 2NO(g)</formula></paragraph>
              </question>
              <answer>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">i. Dynamic equilibrium: Forward and reverse reactions occur at equal rates, constant macroscopic properties, ongoing molecular activity. Static equilibrium: No movement or reaction in either direction, forces are balanced.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">ii. Since electrolysis requires energy input, the decomposition is endothermic. Increasing temperature will favor the forward (endothermic) direction, producing more <formula type="chemical">H₂</formula> and <formula type="chemical">O₂</formula>.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iii. By applying Le Châtelier's Principle: adjust temperature (low for exo, high for endo forward), adjust pressure (high P for fewer gas moles of product, low P for more), add excess reactants, or continuously remove products.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iv. Use a catalyst, increase temperature (though this may affect yield), increase reactant concentrations, or increase surface area for heterogeneous reactions.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">v. No effect on equilibrium position, as there are 2 moles of gas on both reactant and product sides.</emphasis></paragraph>
              </answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="6.3.ex12" level="advanced" title="Constructed Response Questions">
              <question>
                  <paragraph>i. Why are some reactions irreversible while others are reversible?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>ii. Why are combustion reactions generally irreversible?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>iii. Can you make an irreversible reaction reversible and vice versa?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>iv. How do you know if a reaction is reversible or irreversible experimentally?</paragraph>
                  <paragraph>v. Are the phase changes in water (solid to liquid, liquid to vapour) reversible or irreversible?</paragraph>
              </question>
              <answer>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">i. Reversibility depends on whether products can react under the same conditions to reform reactants, and the activation energies for both forward and reverse reactions. If products are very stable or escape, or if reverse activation energy is too high, it's practically irreversible.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">ii. Combustion reactions usually produce very stable products like <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> and <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>, and are highly exothermic. The reverse reaction would be highly endothermic with a very high activation energy, making it non-spontaneous under normal conditions.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iii. Yes, by changing conditions. An irreversible reaction might become reversible under extreme conditions (e.g., very high T to decompose <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>). A reversible one can be made to go to completion by removing a product.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iv. Experimentally, if after some time all reactants and products are present and their concentrations are constant, it's reversible at equilibrium. If reactants are fully consumed to form products, it's irreversible.</emphasis></paragraph>
                  <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">v. Phase changes of water are reversible physical changes. Ice melts to water, water freezes to ice; water boils to steam, steam condenses to water, all by changing temperature/pressure.</emphasis></paragraph>
              </answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch6-topic6.3-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Industrial Chemistry">
          <paragraph>The principles of manipulating chemical equilibria directly apply to large-scale industrial processes. The Haber process for ammonia production specifically uses high pressure (200 atm) and moderate temperature (400-450°C) with an iron catalyst to optimize yield while maintaining reasonable reaction rates.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch6-topic6.3-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Everyday Chemistry">
          <paragraph>Phase equilibria between solid, liquid, and gas states govern many familiar processes. The equilibrium between water vapor in air and liquid water determines humidity levels and weather phenomena like dew formation.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch6-topic6.3-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Biology">
          <paragraph>Biological systems use Le Châtelier's Principle constantly. For example, hemoglobin's oxygen-binding equilibrium shifts depending on <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> concentration (the Bohr effect), enabling efficient oxygen delivery to tissues with high metabolic activity.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="6.3.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Deep-Sea Chemistry: At the bottom of oceans, the extremely high pressure shifts carbonate equilibria enough to dissolve calcium carbonate shells that would be stable at surface pressures, creating unique deep-sea ecosystems.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="6.3.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Diamond Formation: Diamonds form from carbon at extremely high pressures deep in Earth's mantle. According to Le Châtelier's Principle, the high-pressure environment favors diamond (more dense) over graphite (less dense) in the equilibrium between these carbon forms.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="6.3.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. Colorful Demonstrations: Chemistry teachers often demonstrate Le Châtelier's Principle using cobalt chloride equilibrium. By changing temperature or adding water, they can make solutions dramatically shift between pink and blue colors, illustrating equilibrium shifts visually!</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>

