      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.1-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="pH Scale">
          <paragraph>Understanding acids and bases leads directly to the pH scale, which quantifies the strength of acids and bases based on the concentration of hydrogen ions in solution.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.1-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Salt Formation">
          <paragraph>The study of acids and bases connects to salt chemistry, as neutralization reactions between acids and bases produce various salts with different properties and applications.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.1-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Buffer Solutions">
          <paragraph>Knowledge of acids and bases is essential for understanding buffer solutions, which resist changes in pH and play crucial roles in biological systems and chemical processes.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.1.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Formic acid, found in ant stings, got its name from the Latin word "formica," meaning ant. When an ant stings, it injects this acid into your skin, causing the burning sensation.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.1.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Citrus fruits contain citric acid, which not only gives them their sour taste but also acts as a natural preservative, extending the shelf life of many foods.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.1.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. Your stomach contains hydrochloric acid with a pH of about 1.5-3.5, strong enough to dissolve metal, but is protected by a special mucous lining that prevents the acid from damaging the stomach itself.</paragraph>
        </content>
