    <topic id="ch7-topic7.2" title="Different Concepts of Acids and Bases">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Arrhenius defined acids as substances that produce hydrogen ions (H+) in water and bases as substances that produce hydroxide ions (OH-) in water, establishing the first molecular explanation for acid-base behavior.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Arrhenius Acid: HCl in water dissociating into H⁺ and Cl⁻ (H⁺ then forms H₃O⁺ with water). Arrhenius Base: NaOH in water dissociating into Na⁺ and OH⁻. - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          While the traditional definitions of acids and bases describe their distinctive features, scientists needed broader definitions to explain their chemical behavior at the molecular level. Svante Arrhenius, a Swedish chemist, proposed definitions based on how these substances behave in water.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          According to Arrhenius, an <emphasis type="bold">acid</emphasis> is a substance that dissociates in water to produce protons (H+) or hydronium ions (<formula type="chemical">H₃O+</formula>). Examples include HCl, <formula type="chemical">HNO₃</formula>, <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>, and HCN. When these acids dissolve in water, they release H+ ions, which immediately combine with water molecules to form hydronium ions (<formula type="chemical">H₃O+</formula>) due to the high charge density of the proton.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          Similarly, Arrhenius defined a <emphasis type="bold">base</emphasis> as a substance that dissociates in water to produce hydroxyl ions (OH-). Common examples include NaOH, KOH, and <formula type="chemical">Ba(OH)₂</formula>. In Arrhenius's concept, water plays an essential role, as it interacts with the dissociated ions.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          Since a proton is very small in size and its charge density is very high, it forms a strong bond with the lone pair of a water molecule to give a hydronium ion, <formula type="chemical">H₃O+</formula>. It is reported that up to four water molecules may surround the proton. Similarly, hydroxyl ions are also surrounded by water molecules.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Diagram showing H⁺ ion surrounded by multiple water molecules (solvation/hydration of H⁺ to H₃O⁺ and further hydration). - necessity_score: 6/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p5" type="paragraph">
          Arrhenius also explained the process of <emphasis type="bold">neutralization</emphasis>. According to him, when a strong acid and a strong base are dissolved in water, they completely dissociate into ions. The hydronium ion and the hydroxyl ion then react to form water with the evolution of heat. For instance, with HCl and NaOH, the salt NaCl formed remains dissociated in solution as hydrated spectator ions (<formula type="chemical">Na⁺(aq)</formula> and <formula type="chemical">Cl⁻(aq)</formula>).
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p6" type="paragraph">
          The <emphasis type="bold">strength of an acid</emphasis> depends on the extent to which it is ionized in water. Strong acids like hydrochloric acid ionize completely in water, producing a large concentration of hydronium ions. Sulfuric acid, being a diprotic acid, ionizes in two steps. Weak acids like acetic acid ionize only partially. Glacial acetic acid has a percent ionization of only 0.132%; out of 1000 molecules of acetic acid, only about 1.32 molecules dissociate. Similarly, the percent ionization of formic acid (1.50M) is 1.06%.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p7" type="paragraph">
          Similarly, bases can be strong or weak. <emphasis type="bold">Strong bases</emphasis> like NaOH and KOH ionize completely in water. <emphasis type="bold">Weak bases</emphasis> like <formula type="chemical">NH₄OH</formula> (aqueous ammonia) and <formula type="chemical">Al(OH)₃</formula> ionize only partially. For example, <formula type="chemical">NH₄OH(aq) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq)</formula>.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exp-p8" type="paragraph">
          <emphasis type="bold">Stomach Acidity</emphasis>: Our stomach produces hydrochloric acid to digest food. Hyperacidity occurs when more acid is produced than needed, often due to fatty or spicy foods, causing a burning sensation. Antacids, containing weak bases like calcium hydroxide or magnesium hydroxide, neutralize this excess acid. The concentration of hydroxyl ions in antacids is low enough not to harm the throat or stomach.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Swimming Pool Analogy">
          <paragraph>Think of dissociation like people jumping into a swimming pool. Strong acids are like a team of professional divers who all jump in at once (complete dissociation). Weak acids are like hesitant swimmers - only a few jump in while most stay on the edge (partial dissociation). The more swimmers in the pool (ions in solution), the stronger the acid or base.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Two swimming pools: one with many divers in water (strong acid), one with few divers in water and many on edge (weak acid). - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="The Puzzle Piece Analogy">
          <paragraph>Imagine acid molecules as puzzle pieces that can break apart in water. Strong acids are like puzzles that completely fall apart into their individual pieces (ions) when placed in water. Weak acids are like puzzles where most pieces stay connected and only a few break away. The more pieces that separate, the stronger the acid.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Strong vs. Weak Acid Dissociation">
          <paragraph>Hydrochloric acid (strong): <formula type="chemical">HCl(aq) + H₂O(l) → H₃O⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq)</formula> (Complete dissociation)</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Acetic acid (weak): <formula type="chemical">CH₃COOH(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ H₃O⁺(aq) + CH₃COO⁻(aq)</formula> (Only 0.132% dissociation for glacial acetic acid, which is concentrated. Dilute solutions will have higher percent ionization.)</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Neutralization of Stomach Acid">
          <paragraph>Excess hydrochloric acid (HCl) in the stomach causing hyperacidity can be neutralized by an antacid containing magnesium hydroxide <formula type="chemical">Mg(OH)₂</formula>:</paragraph>
          <paragraph><formula type="chemical">2HCl(aq) + Mg(OH)₂(s) → MgCl₂(aq) + 2H₂O(l)</formula></paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Battery Acid">
          <paragraph>Car batteries use sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>), a strong Arrhenius acid, as an electrolyte. Its ability to produce a high concentration of ions in water is key to battery function.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Drain Cleaners">
          <paragraph>Many liquid drain cleaners contain sodium hydroxide (NaOH), a strong Arrhenius base, which effectively breaks down grease and hair due to its high concentration of OH⁻ ions.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Food Preparation with Vinegar">
          <paragraph>Vinegar contains acetic acid, a weak Arrhenius acid. Its partial ionization provides a mild sour taste and preservative properties without being overly corrosive.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.2.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. If acetic acid has a percent ionization of only 0.132%, calculate how many molecules out of 10,000 acetic acid molecules would be ionized in a solution. What would this number be for formic acid with 1.06% ionization?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.2.ie2">
          <paragraph>2. Design an experiment to compare the strength of different acids (e.g., HCl vs. <formula type="chemical">CH₃COOH</formula>). How would you measure the relative amounts of H₃O⁺ ions produced by equal concentrations of different acids (e.g., using conductivity or pH measurement)?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.2.ie3">
          <paragraph>3. How do chloride ions exist in water after HCl dissociates? (Hint: solvation by water molecules).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.2.ie4">
          <paragraph>4. Why does ammonium hydroxide (<formula type="chemical">NH₄OH</formula>) only partially ionize in water? (Hint: consider the equilibrium <formula type="chemical">NH₃(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq)</formula>).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Arrhenius defined acids as substances that produce H⁺ (or H₃O⁺) ions in water.</point>
          <point>Arrhenius defined bases as substances that produce OH⁻ ions in water.</point>
          <point>Strong acids and bases completely dissociate (ionize) in water.</point>
          <point>Weak acids and bases partially dissociate (ionize) in water.</point>
          <point>Neutralization reactions involve H⁺ (from acid) and OH⁻ (from base) combining to form water.</point>
          <point>The stomach produces HCl for digestion; antacids contain weak bases to neutralize excess acid.</point>
          <point>Percent ionization is a measure of the strength of an acid or base.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
