      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Buffer Solutions">
          <paragraph>Understanding the partial ionization of weak acids and bases (Arrhenius concept) is fundamental to understanding how buffer solutions work to maintain a stable pH.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Chemical Equilibrium">
          <paragraph>The partial dissociation of weak acids and bases is an example of chemical equilibrium, where forward and reverse reactions occur at equal rates.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.2-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Physiological pH Regulation">
          <paragraph>The concept of acid and base strength relates directly to how our bodies maintain proper pH balance, especially in blood and digestive systems, often involving Arrhenius acids and bases.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.2.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Svante Arrhenius, who proposed this acid-base theory, won the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903 - primarily for his theory of electrolytic dissociation, which underpinned his acid-base concepts.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.2.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Wine becomes vinegar when ethanol is oxidized to acetic acid (an Arrhenius weak acid) through bacterial action, which is why wine that's been open too long tastes sour.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.2.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. The term "acid" comes from the Latin word "acidus," meaning sour or sharp. Ancient Romans used to use sour wine (vinegar) as a primitive cleaning solution due to its acidic properties.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
