    <topic id="ch7-topic7.3" title="Bronsted-Lowry Concepts of Acids and Bases">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          According to the Bronsted-Lowry concept, an acid is a proton (H+) donor and a base is a proton acceptor, broadening the definition beyond water-based solutions and explaining acid-base behavior in various solvents and even gas-phase reactions.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: General Bronsted-Lowry reaction: Acid(1) + Base(2) ⇌ Conjugate Base(1) + Conjugate Acid(2), showing proton (H⁺) transfer with an arrow. - necessity_score: 10/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          While Arrhenius' concept of acids and bases provided a solid foundation, it had limitations. For example, it couldn't explain why compounds like <formula type="chemical">Na₂CO₃</formula>, <formula type="chemical">K₂CO₃</formula>, and <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>, which don't contain hydroxide groups, still behave as bases in water. Additionally, the Arrhenius definition required water as a solvent, limiting its application.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          To address these limitations, Johannes Bronsted and Thomas Lowry independently proposed a broader definition in 1923. According to their concept:
          An <emphasis type="bold">acid</emphasis> is a substance that donates a proton (H⁺).
          A <emphasis type="bold">base</emphasis> is a substance that accepts a proton (H⁺).
          This definition requires an acid to have a proton to donate, but eliminated the condition of water presence.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          All Arrhenius acids are also Bronsted-Lowry acids (e.g., HCl donates H⁺ to <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> forming <formula type="chemical">H₃O⁺</formula>). All Arrhenius bases are Bronsted-Lowry bases (e.g., OH⁻ readily accepts H⁺). However, species like OH⁻, CN⁻, <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>, and Cl⁻ are all Bronsted-Lowry bases because they can accept a proton, though not all are Arrhenius bases. Note that <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula> is a Bronsted-Lowry base but not an Arrhenius base itself (though its aqueous solution, <formula type="chemical">NH₄OH</formula>, is an Arrhenius base).
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p4" type="paragraph">
          According to Bronsted-Lowry, an acid-base reaction is one in which a proton is transferred from a proton donor to its acceptor. This reaction may take place in the gas phase or in the presence of any solvent.
          Consider: <formula type="chemical">HCl(g) + H₂O(l) → H₃O⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq)</formula>. Here, HCl acts as an acid (donates H⁺) and <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> acts as a base (accepts H⁺).
          Similarly, when ammonia dissolves in water: <formula type="chemical">NH₃(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq)</formula>. Here, <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula> is a base (accepts H⁺ from water) and <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> is an acid (donates H⁺).
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p5" type="paragraph">
          An important concept is <emphasis type="bold">conjugate acid-base pairs</emphasis>. When an acid donates a proton, the species remaining is its conjugate base. When a base accepts a proton, the species formed is its conjugate acid.
          In <formula type="chemical">NH₃(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq)</formula>:
          <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula> (base) and <formula type="chemical">NH₄⁺</formula> (its conjugate acid) form one pair.
          <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> (acid) and <formula type="chemical">OH⁻</formula> (its conjugate base) form another pair.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exp-p6" type="paragraph">
          Water is <emphasis type="bold">amphoteric</emphasis>, meaning it can act as both an acid (donating a proton) and a base (accepting a proton) depending on the substance it reacts with.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Two reactions showing water acting as an acid (with NH3) and as a base (with HCl), highlighting proton transfer. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Hot Potato Analogy">
          <paragraph>Imagine a proton as a hot potato. In acid-base reactions, the acid is like a person who can't hold the hot potato (proton) anymore and quickly passes it to someone else (the base) who's willing to take it. After passing the hot potato, the acid becomes the conjugate base (now "empty-handed" and able to receive it back), and after receiving it, the base becomes the conjugate acid (now "holding the potato" and able to pass it on).</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Animation of a "hot potato" (proton) being passed from an "Acid" figure to a "Base" figure. The figures then transform into their conjugate forms. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="The Donor-Receiver Analogy">
          <paragraph>Think of acids as generous donors who always have an extra proton to give away. Bases are eager receivers with space (often a lone pair of electrons) to accept these protons. In any Bronsted-Lowry acid-base reaction, there's always a donor (acid) passing a proton to a receiver (base). After the exchange, the original donor becomes a potential receiver (conjugate base), and the original receiver becomes a potential donor (conjugate acid).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Ammonia in Water">
          <paragraph><formula type="chemical">NH₃(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + OH⁻(aq)</formula></paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Acid: <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> (donates H⁺)</item>
            <item>Base: <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula> (accepts H⁺)</item>
            <item>Conjugate Acid (of <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>): <formula type="chemical">NH₄⁺</formula></item>
            <item>Conjugate Base (of <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>): OH⁻</item>
          </list>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Hydrogen Chloride in Water">
          <paragraph><formula type="chemical">HCl(g) + H₂O(l) → H₃O⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq)</formula></paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Acid: HCl (donates H⁺)</item>
            <item>Base: <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> (accepts H⁺)</item>
            <item>Conjugate Acid (of <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>): <formula type="chemical">H₃O⁺</formula></item>
            <item>Conjugate Base (of HCl): Cl⁻</item>
          </list>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Buffer Systems in Biology">
          <paragraph>The bicarbonate buffer system in human blood (<formula type="chemical">H₂CO₃ ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻</formula>) is a prime example of Bronsted-Lowry acid-base pairs working to maintain pH. <formula type="chemical">H₂CO₃</formula> is the acid, <formula type="chemical">HCO₃⁻</formula> is its conjugate base.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Explaining Basicity of Salts">
          <paragraph>The Bronsted-Lowry theory explains why salts of weak acids, like sodium acetate (<formula type="chemical">CH₃COONa</formula>), produce basic solutions. The acetate ion (<formula type="chemical">CH₃COO⁻</formula>) acts as a Bronsted-Lowry base, accepting a proton from water.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Organic Reaction Mechanisms">
          <paragraph>Many organic reactions involve proton transfers between molecules. Understanding which species can act as a Bronsted-Lowry acid or base is crucial for predicting reaction pathways.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Acid-Base Titrations">
          <paragraph>While often done in water, the principles of proton transfer apply to titrations in non-aqueous solvents, which are better understood using the Bronsted-Lowry definition.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
