        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Bronsted-Lowry acids are proton (H⁺) donors.</point>
          <point>Bronsted-Lowry bases are proton (H⁺) acceptors.</point>
          <point>This concept is broader than Arrhenius, not limited to aqueous solutions.</point>
          <point>An acid-base reaction involves the transfer of a proton from an acid to a base.</point>
          <point>When an acid donates a proton, it forms its conjugate base.</point>
          <point>When a base accepts a proton, it forms its conjugate acid.</point>
          <point>Amphoteric substances, like water, can act as both a Bronsted-Lowry acid and a base.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="7.3.ex1" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph>1. For the following reaction, identify the acid, base, conjugate acid, and conjugate base: <formula type="chemical">HF(aq) + NH₃(aq) ⇌ NH₄⁺(aq) + F⁻(aq)</formula></paragraph></question>
            <answer>
              <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>:</paragraph>
              <list type="unordered">
                <item>Acid: HF</item>
                <item>Base: <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula></item>
                <item>Conjugate acid (of <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>): <formula type="chemical">NH₄⁺</formula></item>
                <item>Conjugate base (of HF): F⁻</item>
              </list>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.3.ex2" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph>2. Explain why <formula type="chemical">HSO₄⁻</formula> can act as both a Bronsted-Lowry acid and a Bronsted-Lowry base. Write equations to illustrate.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: As an acid: <formula type="chemical">HSO₄⁻(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ SO₄²⁻(aq) + H₃O⁺(aq)</formula> (donates H⁺). As a base: <formula type="chemical">HSO₄⁻(aq) + H₃O⁺(aq) ⇌ H₂SO₄(aq) + H₂O(l)</formula> (accepts H⁺).</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.3.ex3" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>3. Complete the following reaction and identify the conjugate acid-base pairs: <formula type="chemical">CH₃COOH(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ ? + ?</formula></paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: <formula type="chemical">CH₃COOH(aq) + H₂O(l) ⇌ H₃O⁺(aq) + CH₃COO⁻(aq)</formula>. Pairs: <formula type="chemical">CH₃COOH</formula>/<formula type="chemical">CH₃COO⁻</formula> (acid/conjugate base) and <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>/<formula type="chemical">H₃O⁺</formula> (base/conjugate acid).</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.3.ex4" level="intermediate">
            <question>
              <paragraph>4. Which of the following cannot act as a Bronsted-Lowry base? <formula type="chemical">NH₃</formula>, OH⁻, <formula type="chemical">BF₃</formula>, CN⁻</paragraph>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: <formula type="chemical">BF₃</formula>. A Bronsted-Lowry base must be able to accept a proton. This typically requires a lone pair of electrons. <formula type="chemical">BF₃</formula> has an incomplete octet on boron and acts as a Lewis acid (electron pair acceptor), not a proton acceptor.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Acid-Base Equilibria">
          <paragraph>The Bronsted-Lowry concept is fundamental to understanding acid-base equilibria and the calculation of equilibrium constants like Kₐ and K<subscript>b</subscript>.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Lewis Acid-Base Theory">
          <paragraph>The Bronsted-Lowry theory is a subset of the more general Lewis acid-base theory, where acids are electron-pair acceptors and bases are electron-pair donors. All Bronsted-Lowry bases are Lewis bases, but not all Lewis acids are Bronsted-Lowry acids.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.3-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Organic Chemistry Mechanisms">
          <paragraph>Many reaction mechanisms in organic chemistry involve proton transfers, which are described by Bronsted-Lowry acid-base interactions. Identifying acidic protons and basic sites is key to predicting reactivity.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.3.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Johannes Bronsted (Danish) and Thomas Martin Lowry (English) independently proposed their proton-transfer theory of acids and bases in the same year, 1923!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.3.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Thomas Lowry was also interested in optical rotation and studied how the structure of molecules affected their interaction with polarized light, a field important in distinguishing between stereoisomers.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.3.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. The concept of amphoteric substances (like water) being able to act as either an acid or a base is crucial in many biological systems, such as amino acids which contain both acidic (-COOH) and basic (-NH₂) groups.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>

    <topic id="ch7-topic7.4" title="Properties of Acids and Bases">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Acids and bases exhibit distinctive chemical properties: acids react with reactive metals to produce hydrogen gas, with carbonates/bicarbonates to produce carbon dioxide, and with bases/metal oxides in neutralization reactions. Bases react with acids in neutralization reactions and with ammonium salts to produce ammonia gas when heated.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          The properties of acids and bases vary depending on the substances they react with.
          <emphasis type="bold">Properties of Acids:</emphasis> Acids give three main types of reactions:
          <list type="ordered">
            <item>With alkalis or metal oxides, they form salts and water (neutralization). E.g., <formula type="chemical">CuO(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) → CuSO₄(aq) + H₂O(l)</formula>.</item>
            <item>With reactive metals (like Mg, Zn), they form salts and evolve hydrogen gas. E.g., <formula type="chemical">Zn(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) → ZnSO₄(aq) + H₂(g)</formula>. The less reactive metals like Cu, Ag, Au, and Pt do not evolve hydrogen gas with non-oxidizing acids.</item>
            <item>They decompose metal carbonates and hydrogen carbonates, evolving carbon dioxide gas. E.g., <formula type="chemical">Na₂CO₃(s) + 2HCl(aq) → 2NaCl(aq) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g)</formula>.</item>
          </list>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          <emphasis type="bold">Properties of Bases (especially Alkalis):</emphasis> Alkalis are water-soluble bases (e.g., NaOH, KOH). <formula type="chemical">Ca(OH)₂</formula> is sparingly soluble, while <formula type="chemical">Cu(OH)₂</formula> is insoluble.
          Apart from reacting with acids in neutralization reactions, alkalis also react with ammonium salts (when heated) and liberate ammonia gas. E.g., <formula type="chemical">NH₄Cl(s) + NaOH(aq) → NaCl(aq) + H₂O(l) + NH₃(g)</formula>.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          These chemical properties have practical applications. For instance, a mixture of sodium bicarbonate (a weak base) and vinegar (a weak acid) can be used to clear minor drain blockages due to the <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> produced. Caustic chemical drain cleaners (strong bases like NaOH) dissolve grease and hair.
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Chemical Reaction Menu">
          <paragraph>Think of acids and bases as having a "reaction menu." When an acid meets a metal, it "orders" hydrogen gas release. When it meets a carbonate, it "orders" carbon dioxide. When an acid meets a base, they both "order" salt and water (neutralization). Bases also have their menu, like "ordering" ammonia gas when they meet an ammonium salt.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Magnesium Reacting with Hydrochloric Acid">
          <paragraph>When magnesium ribbon is added to dilute hydrochloric acid: <formula type="chemical">Mg(s) + 2HCl(aq) → MgCl₂(aq) + H₂(g)</formula>. Bubbles of hydrogen gas are observed.</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Test tube with magnesium ribbon in HCl, showing bubbles of H2 gas evolving. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Sodium Hydroxide Reacting with Ammonium Chloride">
          <paragraph>When sodium hydroxide solution is heated with ammonium chloride: <formula type="chemical">NaOH(aq) + NH₄Cl(aq) → NaCl(aq) + H₂O(l) + NH₃(g)</formula>. Ammonia gas, with its pungent smell, is released.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Baking with Baking Soda/Powder">
          <paragraph>Baking soda (<formula type="chemical">NaHCO₃</formula>) or baking powder (contains an acid and <formula type="chemical">NaHCO₃</formula>) reacts in batter to produce <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> gas, which causes doughs and batters to rise, making them light and airy.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Cleaning with Acids and Bases">
          <paragraph>Vinegar (acetic acid) is used to remove limescale (<formula type="chemical">CaCO₃</formula>) deposits. Oven cleaners often contain NaOH (a strong base) to break down grease (saponification of fats).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Antacids for Indigestion">
          <paragraph>Antacids are bases (e.g., <formula type="chemical">Mg(OH)₂</formula>, <formula type="chemical">Al(OH)₃</formula>, <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃</formula>) that neutralize excess stomach acid (HCl), relieving heartburn and indigestion.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Metal Cleaning (Pickling)">
          <paragraph>Acids are used in industrial processes called pickling to remove rust or oxide scale from metal surfaces before further processing like plating or painting.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.4.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. Take a few granules of zinc in a clean test tube. Add dilute <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula> in it and heat it gently. Identify the gas evolved in this reaction by taking a burning match stick near the mouth of the test tube. Note the observations in your notebook.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.4.ie2">
          <paragraph>2. How to clean a blocked drain? One way is to pour half a cup of sodium bicarbonate solution into the drain followed by half a cup of vinegar. Cover the drain and wait for thirty minutes. Pour boiling water down the drain. Explain the chemistry involved. Alternatively, caustic chemical drain cleaners (strong bases) are capable of dissolving grease and hair. How does this work through saponification?</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Acids react with alkalis or metal oxides to form salts and water (neutralization).</point>
          <point>Acids react with reactive metals (e.g., Mg, Zn) to form salts and hydrogen gas.</point>
          <point>Acids decompose metal carbonates and hydrogen carbonates, releasing carbon dioxide gas.</point>
          <point>Alkalis are water-soluble bases.</point>
          <point>Bases (alkalis) react with ammonium salts upon heating to release ammonia gas.</point>
          <point>These chemical properties are fundamental to many household and industrial applications.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="7.4.ex1" level="intermediate">
            <question>
              <paragraph>1. Complete and balance the following chemical equations:</paragraph>
              <list type="alpha_ordered">
                <item>a) <formula type="chemical">Mg(s) + HCl(aq) →</formula></item>
                <item>b) <formula type="chemical">Na₂CO₃(s) + HNO₃(aq) →</formula></item>
                <item>c) <formula type="chemical">Ca(OH)₂(aq) + H₃PO₄(aq) →</formula></item>
                <item>d) <formula type="chemical">NH₄Cl(aq) + KOH(aq) (heat) →</formula></item>
              </list>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answers</emphasis>:</paragraph>
              <paragraph>a) <formula type="chemical">Mg(s) + 2HCl(aq) → MgCl₂(aq) + H₂(g)</formula></paragraph>
              <paragraph>b) <formula type="chemical">Na₂CO₃(s) + 2HNO₃(aq) → 2NaNO₃(aq) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g)</formula></paragraph>
              <paragraph>c) <formula type="chemical">3Ca(OH)₂(aq) + 2H₃PO₄(aq) → Ca₃(PO₄)₂(s) + 6H₂O(l)</formula></paragraph>
              <paragraph>d) <formula type="chemical">NH₄Cl(aq) + KOH(aq) → KCl(aq) + H₂O(l) + NH₃(g)</formula> (upon heating)</paragraph>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.4.ex2" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>2. A student adds an unknown metal to dilute sulfuric acid. No reaction is observed. Suggest what the metal might be (e.g., copper, silver).</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: The metal is likely less reactive than hydrogen, such as copper, silver, gold, or platinum.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.4.ex3" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>3. What gas is produced when calcium carbonate reacts with hydrochloric acid? How would you test for this gas?</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Carbon dioxide (<formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>) is produced. It can be tested by bubbling it through limewater (<formula type="chemical">Ca(OH)₂</formula> solution); the limewater will turn milky if <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> is present.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Industrial Chemistry">
          <paragraph>The reactions of acids and bases are fundamental to many industrial processes, including the production of fertilizers, soaps, detergents, and the pickling of metals.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Environmental Science">
          <paragraph>Understanding acid-base reactions helps explain environmental phenomena like acid rain formation and its neutralization, as well as soil pH management.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.4-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Analytical Chemistry">
          <paragraph>Titration, a common analytical technique, uses neutralization reactions between acids and bases to determine unknown concentrations.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.4.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Soap is essentially a salt formed from a fatty acid (from fats/oils) and a strong base (like NaOH). This reaction is called saponification and has been used for millennia!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.4.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Baking powder usually contains both an acidic component (like cream of tartar) and a basic component (sodium bicarbonate). When moisture is added, they react to produce <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> bubbles, making baked goods rise.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>

    <topic id="ch7-topic7.5" title="Acid Rain and its Effects">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Acid rain is precipitation with an unusually low pH (typically between 4.2 and 4.4), formed when air pollutants like sulfur dioxide (<formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula>) and nitrogen oxides (<formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula>) combine with atmospheric moisture to create acidic compounds like sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>) and nitric acid (<formula type="chemical">HNO₃</formula>), which damage ecosystems, buildings, and human health.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Diagram showing sources of SO₂ and NOₓ (factories, cars), their reaction in the atmosphere with water (O₂, H₂O) to form H₂SO₄ and HNO₃, and these acids falling as rain. - necessity_score: 10/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          Acid rain forms when pollutants released into the air, particularly sulfur dioxide (<formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula>) and nitrogen oxides (<formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula>), react with water, oxygen, and other chemicals in the atmosphere. These reactions form sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>) and nitric acid (<formula type="chemical">HNO₃</formula>). These acidic compounds then fall to Earth as wet deposition (rain, snow, fog) or in dry form as acidic gases and particulates.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          The primary source of these pollutants is the burning of fossil fuels in power plants, industrial facilities, and vehicle engines. The chemical reactions involved are:
          <formula type="chemical">SO₂(g) + H₂O(l) → H₂SO₃(aq)</formula> (Sulfurous acid)
          <formula type="chemical">2SO₂(g) + O₂(g) → 2SO₃(g)</formula>
          <formula type="chemical">SO₃(g) + H₂O(l) → H₂SO₄(aq)</formula> (Sulfuric acid)
          <formula type="chemical">2NO₂(g) + H₂O(l) → HNO₃(aq) + HNO₂(aq)</formula> (Nitric acid and Nitrous acid)
          Normal rain has a pH of about 5.6 due to dissolved <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>. Acid rain typically has a pH between 4.2 and 4.4.
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          <emphasis type="bold">Effects of Acid Rain:</emphasis>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Soil</emphasis>: Acid rain makes soil more acidic. It dissolves and washes away essential nutrients (like calcium, magnesium) and can release toxic metals like aluminum, harming plants.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Plants</emphasis>: Damage to vegetation and difficulty in growth due to acidic soil and direct contact.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Aquatic Life</emphasis>: Acidification of water bodies makes them uninhabitable for many aquatic species; fish eggs may not hatch.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Buildings and Structures</emphasis>: Accelerates deterioration of stone (especially limestone/marble) and metal structures. Example: <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) → CaSO₄(aq) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g)</formula>.</item>
          </list>
           <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Infographic showing the various effects of acid rain: on forests (damaged trees), lakes (dead fish), statues/buildings (corrosion). - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Invisible Corrosive Mist">
          <paragraph>Imagine a fine, almost invisible mist that slowly settles over everything. This mist (acid rain) doesn't cause immediate, dramatic damage like a strong acid spill, but over time, it subtly eats away at stone, leaches nutrients from soil, and makes water bodies inhospitable, like a slow-acting corrosive agent affecting the entire environment.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="The Chemical Boomerang">
          <paragraph>Think of acid rain as a chemical boomerang. Industries release pollutants (<formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula>, <formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula>) into the air. These pollutants travel, transform into acids, and eventually return to Earth, often far from their origin, causing damage. What goes up (as pollutants) must come down (as acid rain).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Forest Damage in Europe">
          <paragraph>In the 1980s, extensive forest dieback (Waldsterben) in Germany's Black Forest and other European regions was linked to acid rain, which damaged leaves and acidified soil, harming tree health.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Damage to Historical Monuments">
          <paragraph>The marble of ancient structures like the Parthenon in Greece and the Taj Mahal in India has shown significant erosion and discoloration due to the reaction of calcium carbonate with acidic pollutants in rain.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications (of understanding and combating acid rain)">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Emission Control Systems">
          <paragraph>Technologies like flue-gas desulfurization ("scrubbers") in power plants and catalytic converters in vehicles were developed to reduce <formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula> and <formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula> emissions, the primary precursors to acid rain.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Lake and Soil Remediation">
          <paragraph>Liming, the process of adding calcium carbonate (limestone) or calcium oxide (lime) to acidified lakes and soils, is used to neutralize acidity and help restore damaged ecosystems.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Alternative Energy Sources">
          <paragraph>The problem of acid rain has accelerated the push towards cleaner energy sources like solar, wind, and nuclear power, which do not produce significant <formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula> or <formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula> emissions.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.5.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. Research Challenge: Investigate the impact of acid rain on a specific ecosystem (e.g., a forest, a lake, or a type of crop). What are the chemical changes involved and the biological consequences?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="7.5.ie2">
          <paragraph>2. pH Testing Experiment: Collect rainwater samples over several different rainfall events (if possible and safe). Test their pH using universal indicator paper or a pH meter. Compare your results with the typical pH of normal rain (around 5.6) and acid rain (4.2-4.4). What might explain any variations you observe?</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Acid rain has a pH typically between 4.2 and 4.4.</point>
          <point>It forms from atmospheric <formula type="chemical">SO₂</formula> and <formula type="chemical">NOₓ</formula> reacting with moisture to form sulfuric and nitric acids.</point>
          <point>Main sources are burning fossil fuels.</point>
          <point>Effects include: soil acidification and nutrient leaching, damage to vegetation, acidification of water bodies harming aquatic life, and corrosion of buildings and statues.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="7.5.ex1" level="basic">
            <question><paragraph>1. What two main acids are primarily responsible for acid rain?</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Sulfuric acid (<formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula>) and Nitric acid (<formula type="chemical">HNO₃</formula>).</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.5.ex2" level="intermediate">
            <question><paragraph>2. Explain how acid rain damages buildings made of limestone (<formula type="chemical">CaCO₃</formula>). Write a relevant chemical equation using sulfuric acid as an example.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Acid rain reacts with calcium carbonate, dissolving it. <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) → CaSO₄(aq) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g)</formula>. This chemical weathering causes the stone to erode.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="7.5.ex3" level="advanced" title="Chapter Review Questions (Integrated from source's final questions)">
            <question>
                <paragraph>Descriptive Questions:</paragraph>
                <paragraph>i. Explain Arrhenius concept of acids and bases.</paragraph>
                <paragraph>ii. Compare Arrhenius and Bronsted-Lowry concepts of acids and bases.</paragraph>
                <paragraph>iii. How does sulphuric acid react with the following compounds: <formula type="chemical">NH₄Cl</formula>, <formula type="chemical">NH₄NO₃</formula>, MgO, <formula type="chemical">MgCO₃</formula>? (Write balanced equations where applicable)</paragraph>
                <paragraph>iv. What happens when a base reacts with a non-metallic oxide? What do you infer about the nature of non-metallic oxide?</paragraph>
                <paragraph>v. State the reason for acidic character by both dry HCl gas (when dissolved in appropriate non-aqueous solvent that allows proton donation) and HCl solution in water.</paragraph>
                <paragraph>vi. Differentiate between an acid and its conjugate base.</paragraph>
                <paragraph>Investigative Questions:</paragraph>
                <paragraph>vii. Acids play significant roles within human body. Comment on this statement with examples.</paragraph>
                <paragraph>viii. What is observed when <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> is passed through lime water (i) for a short duration (ii) for a long duration? Write equations.</paragraph>
            </question>
            <answer>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answers (Descriptive):</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">i. Arrhenius: Acids produce H⁺ in water; bases produce OH⁻ in water.</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">ii. Arrhenius is limited to aqueous solutions and specific ion production (H⁺/OH⁻). Bronsted-Lowry is broader: acid is H⁺ donor, base is H⁺ acceptor, applicable in any solvent/phase, introduces conjugate pairs.</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iii. <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula> (strong acid) would protonate bases or displace weaker acids. With MgO (basic oxide): <formula type="chemical">MgO + H₂SO₄ → MgSO₄ + H₂O</formula>. With <formula type="chemical">MgCO₃</formula> (carbonate): <formula type="chemical">MgCO₃ + H₂SO₄ → MgSO₄ + H₂O + CO₂</formula>. With ammonium salts like <formula type="chemical">NH₄Cl</formula> or <formula type="chemical">NH₄NO₃</formula>, a strong non-volatile acid like <formula type="chemical">H₂SO₄</formula> can displace a more volatile acid (HCl, <formula type="chemical">HNO₃</formula>) upon heating: <formula type="chemical">2NH₄Cl + H₂SO₄ (conc, heat) → (NH₄)₂SO₄ + 2HCl(g)</formula>.</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">iv. Base + Non-metallic oxide (acidic oxide) → Salt (+ Water if H is present). E.g., <formula type="chemical">2NaOH + CO₂ → Na₂CO₃ + H₂O</formula>. This infers non-metallic oxides are acidic or acid anhydrides.</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">v. Dry HCl gas can act as an acid if it encounters a substance that can accept a proton (Bronsted-Lowry base). In water, HCl ionizes to form <formula type="chemical">H₃O⁺</formula> ions, which are responsible for its acidic properties (Arrhenius and Bronsted-Lowry).</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">vi. An acid donates a proton to become its conjugate base. A conjugate base is the species that remains after an acid has donated H⁺. They differ by one proton. Example: HCl (acid) and Cl⁻ (conjugate base).</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answers (Investigative):</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">vii. HCl in stomach for digestion; Lactic acid in muscles during exercise; Carbonic acid in blood buffer system; Nucleic acids (DNA/RNA) are essential for genetic information.</emphasis></paragraph>
                <paragraph><emphasis type="italic">viii. (i) Short duration: Limewater (<formula type="chemical">Ca(OH)₂</formula>) turns milky due to formation of insoluble <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃</formula>: <formula type="chemical">Ca(OH)₂(aq) + CO₂(g) → CaCO₃(s) + H₂O(l)</formula>. (ii) Long duration: The milkiness disappears as excess <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> reacts with <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃</formula> and water to form soluble calcium bicarbonate: <formula type="chemical">CaCO₃(s) + H₂O(l) + CO₂(g) → Ca(HCO₃)₂(aq)</formula>.</emphasis></paragraph>
            </answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Atmospheric Chemistry">
          <paragraph>Acid rain is a direct consequence of atmospheric chemical reactions involving pollutants and natural atmospheric components like water and oxygen.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Ecology and Environmental Science">
          <paragraph>The effects of acid rain highlight how chemical pollution can disrupt entire ecosystems, from soil and water chemistry to the health of plants and animals.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch7-topic7.5-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Material Science and Conservation">
          <paragraph>Acid rain's corrosive effects on buildings and statues link chemistry to material science and the conservation of cultural heritage.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.5.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. The term "acid rain" was first coined by Scottish chemist Robert Angus Smith in 1852 after studying rainwater chemistry in Manchester, England, a heavily industrialized city at the time.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.5.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Some of the world's most famous landmarks, like the Parthenon in Athens and the Taj Mahal in India, have suffered significant damage from acid rain, prompting extensive conservation efforts.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="7.5.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. While human pollution is the main cause today, natural events like volcanic eruptions can also release large amounts of sulfur dioxide, leading to natural acid rain events that can affect global climate temporarily.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>
