          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch8-topic8.1-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Atomic Structure">
          <paragraph>The periodic table is directly built upon our understanding of atomic structure. The arrangement of electrons in shells and subshells explains why certain elements share similar properties and why the table has its characteristic shape.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch8-topic8.1-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Chemical Bonding">
          <paragraph>The position of an element in the periodic table helps predict how it will form bonds. Elements on the left tend to lose electrons (forming positive ions and ionic bonds with non-metals), while elements on the right tend to gain or share electrons (forming negative ions or covalent bonds).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch8-topic8.1-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Redox Chemistry">
          <paragraph>The periodic trends in electronegativity and ionization energy directly impact an element's tendency to be oxidized (lose electrons) or reduced (gain electrons), which is fundamental to understanding redox reactions and electrochemistry.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="8.1.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. E.G. Mazurs, a Latvian-American chemist, collected and documented over 700 different published versions of the periodic table throughout history, including circular, spiral, and even three-dimensional designs!</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="8.1.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. The first widely recognized version of the periodic table was created by Dmitri Mendeleev in 1869. He arranged elements by atomic mass and left gaps for yet-to-be-discovered elements, accurately predicting their properties. Later, Henry Moseley (1913) refined it by organizing elements by atomic number.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="8.1.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. When Mendeleev published his table, he predicted the existence and properties of "eka-aluminum" (later discovered as gallium), "eka-boron" (scandium), and "eka-silicon" (germanium) with remarkable accuracy!</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
