  <chapter id="ch9" title="Group Properties and Elements">
    <topic id="ch9-topic9.1" title="Properties of Group 1 Elements">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Group 1 elements, also known as alkali metals (excluding hydrogen), possess an ns¹ electronic configuration in their outermost shell. This configuration makes them highly reactive metals characterized by their tendency to easily lose this single valence electron, their softness, silvery appearance, and increasing reactivity down the group.
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Periodic table highlighting Group 1 elements (Li, Na, K, Rb, Cs, Fr). Bohr models for Li and Na showing the single valence electron. - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          The elements in Group 1 of the periodic table are lithium (Li), sodium (Na), potassium (K), rubidium (Rb), cesium (Cs), and francium (Fr). Hydrogen, though in Group 1, is a non-metal gas and typically excluded when discussing alkali metal properties. The defining characteristic of alkali metals is their common electronic configuration: each has just one electron in its outermost s-orbital (<emphasis type="italic">ns¹</emphasis>). This single valence electron is relatively far from the nucleus and shielded by inner electrons, making it easily lost and resulting in their high reactivity.
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          As we move down Group 1 from lithium to cesium:
          <list type="bulleted">
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Atomic Size Increases:</emphasis> Each successive element adds a new electron shell, significantly increasing the atomic radius. The outermost electron becomes farther from the nucleus.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Reactivity Increases:</emphasis> The increasing distance and shielding make the valence electron easier to remove (lower ionization energy). This explains why reactivity increases dramatically down the group. This is evident in their reactions with water (Li reacts steadily, Na vigorously, K violently, Rb and Cs explosively) and other non-metals like halogens and oxygen.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Physical Properties Change:</emphasis> The increasing atomic size weakens the metallic bonding (interatomic attraction). Consequently, these metals become softer and their melting points decrease down the group. Density generally increases down the group because the increase in atomic mass outpaces the increase in atomic volume (with a slight anomaly for potassium being less dense than sodium).</item>
          </list>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The loosely held Hat Analogy">
          <paragraph>Imagine each alkali metal atom wearing a single hat (the valence electron) on top of many layers of clothing (inner electron shells). As you go down the group, the person (atom) gets taller (more shells). The hat on the taller person is further from their core control (nucleus) and more easily blown off by a gust of wind (a reacting chemical), making taller individuals more likely to "lose their hat" (more reactive).</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Series of figures representing Li, Na, K, each taller than the last, with a single hat on top becoming progressively easier to dislodge. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Reactions with Water">
          <paragraph>Lithium: <formula type="chemical">2Li(s) + 2H₂O(l) → 2LiOH(aq) + H₂(g)</formula> (steady reaction)</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Sodium: <formula type="chemical">2Na(s) + 2H₂O(l) → 2NaOH(aq) + H₂(g)</formula> (vigorous reaction, may melt and scoot on water)</paragraph>
          <paragraph>Potassium: <formula type="chemical">2K(s) + 2H₂O(l) → 2KOH(aq) + H₂(g)</formula> (violent reaction, hydrogen often ignites with a lilac flame)</paragraph>
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Short video clips or sequential images of Li, Na, and K reacting with water, showing increasing vigor. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Physical Properties Comparison (Approximate Values)">
          <paragraph>Comparing three Group 1 elements:</paragraph>
          <list type="unordered">
            <item>Lithium: Melting Point 180.5°C, Density 0.534 g/cm³</item>
            <item>Sodium: Melting Point 97.8°C, Density 0.968 g/cm³</item>
            <item>Potassium: Melting Point 63.5°C, Density 0.856 g/cm³</item>
            <item>Cesium: Melting Point 28.4°C, Density 1.879 g/cm³</item>
          </list>
          <paragraph>This shows decreasing melting points and generally increasing density (except K) down the group.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Lithium in Batteries">
          <paragraph>Lithium is a key component in lightweight, high-energy-density rechargeable batteries used in mobile phones, laptops, and electric vehicles due to its high electropositivity.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Sodium in Street Lighting and Salt">
          <paragraph>Sodium vapor lamps produce bright yellow light efficiently, used in street lighting. Sodium chloride (table salt) is essential for life and used in food preservation and chemical industries.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Potassium in Fertilizers">
          <paragraph>Potassium compounds, like potassium chloride (KCl) and potassium nitrate (<formula type="chemical">KNO₃</formula>), are vital components of agricultural fertilizers, promoting plant growth and health.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-rla-item4" type="application_item" title="Cesium in Atomic Clocks">
          <paragraph>Cesium-133 atoms are used in atomic clocks, which are the most accurate timekeeping devices, forming the basis for Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="9.1.ie1">
          <paragraph>1. Why does rubidium (density 1.532 g/cm³) sink in water while lithium (0.534 g/cm³), sodium (0.968 g/cm³), and potassium (0.856 g/cm³) float? Research the relationship between density and buoyancy to explain this observation.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="9.1.ie2">
          <paragraph>2. Design a hypothetical experiment to safely demonstrate the reactivity trend of Group 1 elements with a common non-metal like chlorine. What safety precautions would be paramount and why?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="9.1.ie3">
          <paragraph>3. If element Francium (Fr) is below cesium in Group 1, what properties (e.g., melting point, reactivity with water, ionization energy) would you predict for it compared to cesium?</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="9.1.ie4">
          <paragraph>4. Group 1 elements are stored under oil rather than exposed to air or in water. Based on their properties, explain why this specific storage method is necessary.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Group 1 elements (alkali metals) have an <emphasis type="italic">ns¹</emphasis> valence electron configuration, making them highly reactive.</point>
          <point>Atomic size and reactivity increase down Group 1.</point>
          <point>Reactions with water become more vigorous down the group (Li < Na < K < Rb < Cs).</point>
          <point>Melting points decrease down the group due to weakening metallic bonding.</point>
          <point>Density generally increases down the group (K is an exception, being less dense than Na).</point>
          <point>Alkali metals react vigorously with halogens and oxygen.</point>
          <point>They form ionic compounds with a +1 oxidation state.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.1-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="9.1.ex1" level="basic"> <!-- Changed from general to basic -->
            <question><paragraph>1. Using the melting points: Li (180.5°C), Na (97.8°C), K (63.5°C), Rb (39.3°C), Cs (28.4°C), calculate the percentage decrease in melting point when moving from Lithium to Cesium.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Total decrease = 180.5°C - 28.4°C = 152.1°C. Percentage decrease = (152.1 / 180.5) * 100% ≈ 84.27%.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="9.1.ex2" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question>
              <paragraph>2. Predict the products and write balanced equations for the reactions of:</paragraph>
