          </exercise>
          <exercise id="9.1.ex4" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>4. Using density values (Li=0.534, Na=0.968, K=0.856, Rb=1.532, Cs=1.879 g/cm³), explain why rubidium sinks in water (density ≈ 1.0 g/cm³) while sodium floats. Calculate the mass of 10 cm³ of rubidium and 10 cm³ of sodium.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Rubidium's density (1.532 g/cm³) is greater than water's density, so it sinks. Sodium's density (0.968 g/cm³) is less than water's, so it floats.
            Mass of 10 cm³ Rb = 10 cm³ * 1.532 g/cm³ = 15.32 g.
            Mass of 10 cm³ Na = 10 cm³ * 0.968 g/cm³ = 9.68 g.</paragraph></answer>
