          <paragraph>3. Transition metals often have high tensile strength. What does "tensile strength" mean, and how is this property utilized in everyday materials made from transition metals (e.g., steel)?</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.3-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Transition elements (Groups 3-12) have partially filled d-orbitals.</point>
          <point>They are hard metals with high densities, melting points, and boiling points.</point>
          <point>They exhibit variable oxidation states.</point>
          <point>Many of their compounds are colored due to d-d electron transitions.</point>
          <point>They form complex ions (coordination compounds).</point>
          <point>Transition metals and their compounds are excellent catalysts (e.g., Fe in Haber process, <formula type="chemical">V₂O₅</formula> in Contact process, Ni in hydrogenation).</point>
          <point>Catalytic converters in cars use Pt, Pd, and Rh.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.3-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="9.3.ex1" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from general to intermediate -->
