          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch9-topic9.3-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Coordination Chemistry">
          <paragraph>The ability of transition metals to form complex ions with ligands is a vast field known as coordination chemistry, crucial in catalysis, biological systems (e.g., hemoglobin), and analytical chemistry.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch9-topic9.3-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Magnetism">
          <paragraph>Many transition metals and their compounds exhibit paramagnetism (attracted to a magnetic field) due to unpaired d-electrons. Some, like iron, cobalt, and nickel, are ferromagnetic.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="9.3.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. The vibrant colors of many gemstones, like ruby (chromium in <formula type="chemical">Al₂O₃</formula>) and sapphire (iron and titanium in <formula type="chemical">Al₂O₃</formula>), are due to trace amounts of transition metal ions.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="9.3.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Hemoglobin, the protein that carries oxygen in your blood, contains an iron(II) ion at its core. This iron ion is what reversibly binds to oxygen molecules.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
