      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.2-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Alkenes and Alkynes">
          <paragraph>Alkanes are saturated. Alkenes (C=C) and alkynes (C≡C) are unsaturated hydrocarbons, making them more reactive, typically undergoing addition reactions rather than the substitution reactions common for alkanes.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.2-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Organic Functional Groups">
          <paragraph>Alkanes form the carbon "skeleton" of many organic molecules. Replacing hydrogen atoms with functional groups (e.g., -OH, -COOH, -NH₂) creates diverse classes of compounds (alcohols, carboxylic acids, amines) with unique properties.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.2-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Petroleum Chemistry and Refining">
          <paragraph>Alkanes are the primary components of crude oil and natural gas. Processes like fractional distillation and cracking are used to separate and convert these alkanes into various fuels and chemical feedstocks.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.2.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>) is a potent greenhouse gas, about 25-30 times more effective at trapping heat than <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> over a 100-year period, though it has a shorter atmospheric lifetime.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.2.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. The "octane rating" of gasoline relates to how smoothly it burns in an engine. Isooctane (2,2,4-trimethylpentane, a highly branched alkane) has an octane rating of 100 and is used as a reference standard.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.2.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. Paraffin wax, used in candles and for sealing jars, is a mixture of long-chain alkanes (typically <formula type="chemical">C₂₀</formula> to <formula type="chemical">C₄₀</formula>).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
