      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.3-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Alkanes are prepared by: (1) Cracking of higher hydrocarbons, (2) Hydrogenation (reduction) of alkenes/alkynes, (3) Reduction of alkyl halides.</point>
          <point>Cracking breaks larger hydrocarbons into smaller ones (e.g., alkanes and alkenes) using heat and catalysts (e.g., zeolite at ~500°C). Naphtha (<formula type="chemical">C₅-C₁₀</formula>) can be cracked.</point>
          <point>Hydrogenation adds <formula type="chemical">H₂</formula> to alkenes/alkynes across multiple bonds using catalysts like Ni, Pt, or Pd (e.g., Ni at 200°C) to form alkanes. Methane cannot be made this way.</point>
          <point>Reduction of alkyl halides (R-X) with nascent hydrogen (e.g., from Zn/HCl) replaces the halogen with hydrogen to form an alkane (R-H).</point>
          <point>These methods are vital for adjusting petroleum product yields and synthesizing specific alkanes.</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.3-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="11.3.ex1" level="basic"> <!-- Changed from reaction_completion to basic -->
            <question>
