          <exercise id="11.3.ex2" level="intermediate"> <!-- Changed from calculation to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>2. If 10.0 grams of ethene (<formula type="chemical">C₂H₄</formula>) undergoes complete hydrogenation to ethane (<formula type="chemical">C₂H₆</formula>), calculate the theoretical mass of ethane produced. (Atomic masses: C=12.01, H=1.008)</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Molar mass <formula type="chemical">C₂H₄</formula> = 2(12.01) + 4(1.008) = 24.02 + 4.032 = 28.052 g/mol.
            Moles of ethene = 10.0g / 28.052 g/mol ≈ 0.3565 mol.
            Reaction is <formula type="chemical">C₂H₄ + H₂ → C₂H₆</formula> (1:1 mole ratio). So, 0.3565 mol of ethane is produced.
            Molar mass <formula type="chemical">C₂H₆</formula> = 2(12.01) + 6(1.008) = 24.02 + 6.048 = 30.068 g/mol.
            Mass of ethane = 0.3565 mol * 30.068 g/mol ≈ 10.72 g.</paragraph></answer>
