    <topic id="ch11-topic11.4" title="Important Reactions of Alkanes">
      <section type="definition" title="Core Definition">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-cd-p1" type="paragraph">
          Alkanes, being saturated hydrocarbons with strong, non-polar C-C and C-H bonds, are generally unreactive (often called "paraffins" for "little affinity"). However, they undergo two main types of important reactions: halogenation (a substitution reaction, typically with chlorine or bromine in the presence of UV light) and combustion (reaction with oxygen, producing carbon dioxide, water, and heat).
        </content>
        <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Methane molecule (CH₄). Arrow 1: + Cl₂/UV light → CH₃Cl + HCl (Halogenation). Arrow 2: + O₂/spark → CO₂ + H₂O + Heat (Combustion). - necessity_score: 9/10] -->
      </section>
      <section type="explanation" title="Explanation">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-exp-p1" type="paragraph">
          Alkanes are known for their low chemical reactivity compared to other organic functional groups. This relative inertness is attributed to:
          <list type="bulleted">
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Non-polar C-C and C-H bonds:</emphasis> The electronegativity difference between carbon (2.55) and hydrogen (2.20) is small, resulting in bonds with very little polarity. This means there are no significant positive or negative centers in alkane molecules to attract common ionic or polar reagents like acids, bases, or oxidizing/reducing agents.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Strong Sigma Bonds:</emphasis> The C-C and C-H single bonds (sigma bonds) are strong and require considerable energy to break.</item>
            <item><emphasis type="bold">Saturation:</emphasis> Alkanes are saturated, meaning they have no double or triple bonds (sites of high electron density) or lone pairs that could serve as points of attack for many reagents.</item>
          </list>
          Despite this general unreactivity, alkanes participate in a few important reactions under specific conditions.
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-exp-p2" type="paragraph">
          <emphasis type="bold">1. Halogenation (Substitution Reaction):</emphasis>
          Alkanes react with halogens (typically chlorine, <formula type="chemical">Cl₂</formula>, or bromine, <formula type="chemical">Br₂</formula>) in the presence of ultraviolet (UV) light or high temperatures. This reaction proceeds via a free-radical mechanism and involves the substitution of one or more hydrogen atoms of the alkane with halogen atoms.
          For example, the chlorination of methane (<formula type="chemical">CH₄</formula>) can occur in steps:
          <formula type="chemical">CH₄ + Cl₂ --(UV)→ CH₃Cl (Chloromethane) + HCl</formula>
          <formula type="chemical">CH₃Cl + Cl₂ --(UV)→ CH₂Cl₂ (Dichloromethane) + HCl</formula>
          <formula type="chemical">CH₂Cl₂ + Cl₂ --(UV)→ CHCl₃ (Trichloromethane/Chloroform) + HCl</formula>
          <formula type="chemical">CHCl₃ + Cl₂ --(UV)→ CCl₄ (Tetrachloromethane/Carbon tetrachloride) + HCl</formula>
          Controlling the reaction to obtain a specific chlorinated product can be difficult as a mixture often results.
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-exp-p3" type="paragraph">
          <emphasis type="bold">2. Combustion:</emphasis>
          Alkanes readily burn in excess oxygen to produce carbon dioxide (<formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>) and water (<formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>), releasing a large amount of heat. This exothermic reaction is why alkanes are excellent fuels.
          General equation for complete combustion: <formula type="chemical">CₙH₂ₙ₊₂ + ((3n+1)/2)O₂ → nCO₂ + (n+1)H₂O + Heat</formula>
          Example (methane): <formula type="chemical">CH₄(g) + 2O₂(g) → CO₂(g) + 2H₂O(g) + Heat</formula>
          If oxygen is limited, incomplete combustion can occur, producing carbon monoxide (CO) and/or soot (carbon) instead of or in addition to <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>. Methane-air mixtures can be explosive within certain concentration ranges (typically 5-15% methane in air), which is why gas leaks are hazardous.
          <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Animation of methane combustion, showing CH₄ and O₂ molecules breaking apart and reforming into CO₂ and H₂O, with energy release depicted. - necessity_score: 8/10] -->
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="analogies" title="Analogies & Visualizations">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-av-item1" type="analogy" title="The Well-Guarded Fortress Analogy (Inertness)">
          <paragraph>Think of an alkane molecule as a well-guarded fortress with strong, smooth walls (non-polar sigma bonds). Most common attackers (reagents) can't find a weak spot or a way in. Only very aggressive attackers (like halogen radicals under UV light) or a complete "siege by fire" (combustion) can break it down.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-av-item2" type="analogy" title="The Tag Game Analogy (Halogenation)">
          <paragraph>Halogenation is like a game of tag where chlorine atoms (the "taggers," activated by UV light) chase hydrogen atoms on an alkane. When a chlorine "tags" a hydrogen, it takes its place, and the hydrogen leaves with another chlorine. This can happen multiple times until many hydrogens are replaced.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="examples" title="Examples">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-ex-item1" type="example_item" title="Stepwise Chlorination of Methane">
          <paragraph>As shown in the explanation, methane can be progressively chlorinated:
          <formula type="chemical">CH₄ → CH₃Cl → CH₂Cl₂ → CHCl₃ → CCl₄</formula>
          Each step produces HCl as a byproduct. Controlling the ratio of methane to chlorine and reaction time can influence the product distribution.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-ex-item2" type="example_item" title="Complete Combustion of Propane (LPG)">
          <paragraph>Propane (<formula type="chemical">C₃H₈</formula>), a common fuel in LPG, burns completely in oxygen:
          <formula type="chemical">C₃H₈(g) + 5O₂(g) → 3CO₂(g) + 4H₂O(g) + Heat</formula>
          This reaction releases substantial energy used for cooking and heating.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="real_life_applications" title="Real-Life Applications">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-rla-item1" type="application_item" title="Fuels (Combustion)">
          <paragraph>The combustion of alkanes (methane in natural gas, propane/butane in LPG, octane in gasoline, longer chains in diesel/kerosene) is the primary way we generate energy for heating, cooking, transportation, and electricity production.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-rla-item2" type="application_item" title="Production of Halogenated Solvents and Intermediates (Halogenation)">
          <paragraph>Halogenation of alkanes produces important solvents like dichloromethane (<formula type="chemical">CH₂Cl₂</formula>) and chloroform (<formula type="chemical">CHCl₃</formula>), and chemical intermediates like chloromethane (<formula type="chemical">CH₃Cl</formula>) used in the synthesis of silicones. Carbon tetrachloride (<formula type="chemical">CCl₄</formula>) was formerly used in fire extinguishers and as a dry-cleaning solvent (now phased out due to toxicity/ozone depletion).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-rla-item3" type="application_item" title="Gas Safety (Combustion)">
          <paragraph>Understanding the explosive limits of methane-air mixtures is crucial for designing safety features for natural gas appliances and leak detection systems in homes and industries.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="interactive_elements" title="Interactive Elements">
        <content type="interactive_prompt" id="11.4.ie1">
