          <paragraph>3. Safety Investigation: Methane-air mixtures can be explosive between approximately 5% and 15% methane by volume. Research how natural gas detectors work and what concentration they typically alarm at to prevent dangerous buildups.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="key_points" title="Key Points & Summary">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-kps-list1" type="key_points_list">
          <point>Alkanes are relatively unreactive ("paraffins") due to strong, non-polar C-C and C-H bonds.</point>
          <point>Major reactions are halogenation (substitution) and combustion.</point>
          <point>Halogenation (e.g., with <formula type="chemical">Cl₂</formula> or <formula type="chemical">Br₂</formula>) requires UV light or high temperature and proceeds via a free-radical mechanism, leading to a mixture of halogenated products.</point>
          <point>Combustion is a highly exothermic reaction with oxygen, producing <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula> and <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula> (complete combustion) or CO/C (incomplete combustion if <formula type="chemical">O₂</formula> is limited).</point>
          <point>Methane-air mixtures are explosive within certain concentration limits.</point>
          <point>The inertness of alkanes makes them good solvents for non-polar substances but limits their direct use as chemical feedstocks without prior activation (e.g., via halogenation or cracking).</point>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="exercises" title="Exercises">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-exc-block1" type="exercise_block">
          <exercise id="11.4.ex1" level="basic"> <!-- basic_substitution changed to basic -->
            <question>
              <paragraph>1. Complete the following reaction for the first step of chlorination and name the major organic product: <formula type="chemical">CH₃CH₂CH₃(g) + Cl₂(g) --(UV light)→ ? + HCl(g)</formula></paragraph>
            </question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: A mixture of <formula type="chemical">CH₃CH₂CH₂Cl</formula> (1-chloropropane) and <formula type="chemical">CH₃CHClCH₃</formula> (2-chloropropane) + HCl. 2-chloropropane is typically the major product because the secondary hydrogen is more easily abstracted by a chlorine radical than a primary hydrogen.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="11.4.ex2" level="intermediate"> <!-- combustion_calculation changed to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>2. Write the balanced chemical equation for the complete combustion of butane (<formula type="chemical">C₄H₁₀</formula>). How many moles of oxygen gas are required to completely combust 2.0 moles of butane?</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: <formula type="chemical">2C₄H₁₀(g) + 13O₂(g) → 8CO₂(g) + 10H₂O(g)</formula>. From the balanced equation, 2 moles of butane require 13 moles of <formula type="chemical">O₂</formula>.</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="11.4.ex3" level="advanced"> <!-- oxidation_reduction_analysis changed to advanced -->
            <question><paragraph>3. In the free-radical chlorination of methane, outline the three main steps of the mechanism (initiation, propagation, termination). Provide an example reaction for each step.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>:
            <emphasis type="bold">Initiation:</emphasis> <formula type="chemical">Cl₂ --(UV light)→ 2Cl•</formula> (Chlorine radicals formed)
            <emphasis type="bold">Propagation:</emphasis> (1) <formula type="chemical">Cl• + CH₄ → HCl + •CH₃</formula> (Methyl radical formed)
                               (2) <formula type="chemical">•CH₃ + Cl₂ → CH₃Cl + Cl•</formula> (Chloromethane formed, Cl radical regenerated)
            <emphasis type="bold">Termination:</emphasis> (e.g.) <formula type="chemical">Cl• + Cl• → Cl₂</formula>; or <formula type="chemical">•CH₃ + Cl• → CH₃Cl</formula>; or <formula type="chemical">•CH₃ + •CH₃ → C₂H₆</formula> (Radicals combine to form stable molecules)
            </paragraph></answer>
            <!-- [ILLUSTRATION_NEEDED: Diagram showing the free-radical mechanism steps (initiation, propagation, termination) for chlorination of methane. - necessity_score: 7/10] -->
          </exercise>
          <exercise id="11.4.ex4" level="intermediate"> <!-- bond_analysis changed to intermediate -->
            <question><paragraph>4. During the complete combustion of ethane (<formula type="chemical">C₂H₆</formula>), list all types of chemical bonds that are broken in the reactants and all types of chemical bonds that are formed in the products.</paragraph></question>
            <answer><paragraph><emphasis type="italic">Answer</emphasis>: Bonds Broken: C-C single bonds (in <formula type="chemical">C₂H₆</formula>), C-H single bonds (in <formula type="chemical">C₂H₆</formula>), O=O double bonds (in <formula type="chemical">O₂</formula>). Bonds Formed: C=O double bonds (in <formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>), O-H single bonds (in <formula type="chemical">H₂O</formula>).</paragraph></answer>
          </exercise>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="connections" title="Connections">
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-conn-item1" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Organic Synthesis">
          <paragraph>The halogenation of alkanes, although often producing mixtures, is a key first step to introduce reactivity into an otherwise inert alkane chain. The resulting alkyl halides are versatile intermediates for synthesizing a wide range of other organic compounds (alcohols, amines, ethers, etc.).</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-conn-item2" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Reaction Mechanisms">
          <paragraph>The free-radical halogenation of alkanes is a classic example of a chain reaction mechanism, involving initiation, propagation, and termination steps. Understanding this mechanism provides insight into other radical-based chemical processes.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content id="ch11-topic11.4-sec-conn-item3" type="connection_item" title="Connection to Energy and Environment">
          <paragraph>The combustion of alkanes is central to energy production from fossil fuels. Understanding these reactions is crucial for analyzing energy efficiency, calculating heat output, and addressing environmental impacts like greenhouse gas (<formula type="chemical">CO₂</formula>) emissions and pollutants from incomplete combustion (CO, soot).</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section type="fun_facts" title="Fun Facts & Trivia">
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.4.ff1">
          <paragraph>1. Natural Gas Safety: Pure natural gas (methane) is odorless. Utility companies add trace amounts of pungent sulfur compounds called mercaptans (like ethanethiol) to give it a distinct "rotten egg" smell, allowing for easy detection of dangerous gas leaks.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.4.ff2">
          <paragraph>2. Chloroform (<formula type="chemical">CHCl₃</formula>), a product of methane chlorination, was one of the first widely used anesthetics in surgery during the 19th century, though its use declined due to toxicity concerns.</paragraph>
        </content>
        <content type="fun_fact_item" id="11.4.ff3">
          <paragraph>3. Carbon tetrachloride (<formula type="chemical">CCl₄</formula>), the fully chlorinated derivative of methane, was once common in fire extinguishers (for electrical fires) and as a dry-cleaning solvent, but it's now largely banned due to its toxicity and role in ozone layer depletion.</paragraph>
        </content>
      </section>
    </topic>
